{"title_page": "SS Op Ten Noort", "text_new": "{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image=File:S.S. Op ten Noort van de KPM, Bestanddeelnr 935-3124.jpg\n| Ship caption=SS ''Op Ten Noort'' as passenger ship\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header=\n| Ship country= \n| Ship flag= {{NLD}}\n| Ship name=\n*SS ''Op Ten Noort'' \n* (after stolen: HMHS ''Tenno Maru'')\n*(Before sinking HMHS ''Hikawa Maru No.2'')\n| Ship namesake= \n*Up North \n* (Emperor Circle)\n*([[Hikawa Shrine (Saitama)|Hikawa Shrine, Saitama]])\n| Ship owner=[[Koninklijke Paketvaart-Maatschappij]]\n| Ship operator=\n*Koninklijke Paketvaart-Maatschappij\n*[[Royal Netherlands Navy]] \n*[[Imperial Japanese Navy]] \n| Ship registry=\n| Ship route=[[Dutch East Indies]]\n| Ship ordered=\n| Ship awarded=\n| Ship builder= [[Nederlandsche Scheepsbouw Maatschappij]]\n| Ship original cost=\n| Ship yard number=\n| Ship way number= \n| Ship laid down= \n| Ship launched= February 12, 1927  \n| Ship sponsor=\n| Ship christened=\n| Ship completed= November 9, 1927\n| Ship acquired=\n| Ship commissioned= February 14, 1942 as [[hospital ship]]\n| Ship decommissioned=\n| Ship in service=\n| Ship out of service=\n| Ship renamed=\n| Ship reclassified=\n| Ship refit=\n| Ship struck=\n| Ship reinstated=\n| Ship homeport=[[Java]]\n| Ship identification=PKEA\n| Ship motto=  \n| Ship nickname=\n| Ship honors=\n| Ship captured= February 21, 1941\n| Ship fate=17 August 1945 Scuttled at [[Wakasa Bay]] to cover up  [[Japanese war crimes|war crimes]]\n| Ship notes=\n| Ship badge=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header=\n| Header caption=\n| Ship class=  \n| Ship tonnage=\n| Ship displacement={{convert|6076|LT|MT}}\n| Ship height=\n|Ship length={{Convert|129.5|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{Convert|16.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship draft= {{Convert|6.7|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship depth=\n| Ship hold depth=\n| Ship decks=\n| Ship deck clearance=\n| Ship power=5 Coal boilers \n| Ship propulsion= \n*Two [[Hugo Lentz]] [[Reciprocating engine]]s [[Steam engine|steam]]\n*{{Convert|6000|hp|abbr=on}}\n*Two screws\n| Ship speed={{Convert|15|kn|lk=in}}\n| Ship range=\n| Ship endurance=\n| Ship boats=14 Life boats\n| Ship capacity=\n| Ship troops=\n| Ship complement=\n| Ship crew=162\n| Ship time to activate=\n| Ship sensors=\n| Ship EW=\n| Ship armament=none\n| Ship armor=none\n| Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n[[File:Mailboot SS Op ten Noord van de KPM in de haven van Tandjong Priok, Bestanddeelnr 934-8087.jpg|right|thumb|SS ''Op ten Noord'' in 1931 at [[Tanjung Priok]] in Indonesia, Dutch East Indies]]\n[[File:Het passagiersschip s.s. Op ten Noort van de Koninklijke Paketvaart Mij. (KPM), Bestanddeelnr 935-3116.jpg|right|thumb|SS ''Op ten Noort'' as passenger ship of [[Koninklijke Paketvaart-Maatschappij]] in the port of Surabaya Annotation in 1941]]\n[[File:StateLibQld 1 148207 Op Ten Noort (ship).jpg|right|thumb|SS ''Op ten Noort'']]\n\nThe '''SS ''Op ten Noort''''' was a luxury [[Passenger ship]] built by [[Nederlandsche Scheepsbouw Maatschappij]] in [[Amsterdam]], [[Netherlands]] and completed in 1927. The ship was built for and owned by [[Koninklijke Paketvaart-Maatschappij]] (Royal Packet Navigation Company). Op ten Noort means ''Up North''. In December of 1941 she became a [[Royal Netherlands Navy]] [[hospital ship]]. The [[Empire of Japan]] shortly after her conversion stole the ship and renamed her the '''HMHS ''Tenno Maru'''''. Before sinking her, she was renamed again to the '''HMHS ''Hikawa Maru No.2''''', after the [[Hikawa Shrine (Saitama)|Hikawa Shrine, Saitama]]. To cover up the [[Japanese war crimes|war crimes]] against the ship and her medical crew, at the end of the war, she was sunk on August 17, 1945.<ref>[http://ssmaritime.com/SS-Op-Ten-Noort-plan.htm SS ''Op ten Noort, plans]</ref> \n\n==Dutch East Indies==\nAs a luxury Passenger ship, the ''Op ten Noort'' was put to service in the what was called [[Dutch East Indies]], now [[Indonesia]]. Koninklijke Paketvaart Maatschappij headquarters were in [[Java]] at this time. ''Op ten Noort'' moved both passengers and [[cargo]] on the very profitable routes. On November 9, 1927 she had here [[List of maiden voyages|maid voyage]].  Her 1927 route was from [[Singapore]] to [[Bangkok]] to [[Saigon]] to [[Manila]] to [[Maluku Island]] to [[Bali]] to [[Jakarta]]. A few years the route changed to [[Java]] to [[Batavia, Dutch East Indies|Batavia]] to [[Muntok]] to [[Belawan]] to [[Deli Serdang Regency]]. ''Op ten Noort'' had a sister ship, the SS Plancius that operated in the [[South Pacific Ocean|South Pacific]] also. For fourteen years she serviced these towns as luxury ship. The 130 [[First class travel|First Class]] [[Cabin (ship)|cabins]] had access to lounges, bars, [[smoking room]] and a Tropical [[Verandah]]. For the very wealthy there were two Deluxe Suites with lounge, bedroom, two bathrooms, private deck (Veranda).  She had 18 [[Travel class|Second Class]] 18 cabins. They was for day passenger a [[Tweendeck]] and a [[cafeteria]].\n\n==World war 2==\nWith the outbreak of [[World war 2]] the SS ''Op Ten Noort'' was taken over by the Royal Dutch Navy in December of 1941 as she docked in Jakarta. There she was refit into a hospital ship. She was painted all white ship, with huge red crosses. The Dutch Government officially reported the [[Japanese Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] at the [[Swedish embassy]] in [[Tokyo]] of the change to SS ''Op Ten Noort''. She was now an operational hospital ship, as thus would not be part of the war effort, that is would not transport any weapons or active troops. On February 4, 1942 The Japanese Ministry of Foreign Affairs and [[Ministry of the Navy (Japan)|Naval Ministry]] acknowledges ''Op Ten Noort'' status change though the Swedish embassy. On February 21, 1941, completed she departed on her first trip to help wounded [[Allies of World War II|allies]]. But only a few hours out of port, the ''Op Ten Noort'' was bombed by the Empire of Japan in the [[Java Sea]]. One surgeon and three nurses were killed, eleven were badly wounded. Dutch Government sent a strong note of protest of the bombing to the Japan, through the Embassy of Sweden. After repairs, on 28 February 1942 she was commandeered by the [[Japanese destroyer Amatsukaze (1939)|Japanese destroyer Amatsukaze]] near [[Bawean Island]], stopping her rescue work again. Japanese forced her crew to transport their [[POW]]s to [[List of Japanese-run internment camps during World War II|Japan POW camps]]. The first POW move was that of 59 POWs from the [[USS Perch (SS-176)|USS ''Perch'']] that were on the [[Japanese destroyer Ushio (1930)|Japanese destroyer ''Ushi'']]. By the end of March 1942 she had 970 POWs, most from the 800 survivors from [[HMS Exeter (68)|HMS ''Exeter'']] that sank on March 1, 1942. The [[Prisoner of war|prisoners of war]] were kept in very poor conditions and feed only a cup of rice a day, called [[List of Japanese hell ships|Japanese hell ships]].  <ref>[https://www.britain-at-war.org.uk/WW2/Alf_King/html/japanese_pow.htm Japanese POW by Alf King]</ref> On 20 December 1942 she became the HMHS ''Tenno Maru'' an official Japanese Hospital Ship. The Dutch ship crew was taken off the ship and became POWs at Camp Myoshi, near [[Yokohama]]. Japan had signed the [[Hague Convention of 1907|Hague Convention X of 1907]] that stated attacking a hospital ship is a war crime.<ref name=\"hague10\">{{cite web |date= October 18, 1907|url = http://avalon.law.yale.edu/20th_century/hague10.asp|title = Convention for the adaptation to maritime war of the principles of the Geneva Convention|publisher = [[Yale University]]| accessdate = August 2, 2009 | last= |quote=}}</ref><ref>[https://archive.vn/20130616131847/http://www.minbuza.nl/en/key-topics/treaties/search-the-treaty-database/1899/7/002339.html Convention for the adaptation to maritime warfare of the principles of the Geneva Convention of 22 August 1864]</ref><ref>[http://www.combinedfleet.com/Hikawa2_t.htm combinedfleet.com ''Hikawa Maru No.2''] </ref>\n\nWith the war coming to an end, the ship was changed in October of 1944. A second dummy smokestack was added to \"hide her\". She was renamed the HMHS ''Hikawa Maru No.2''. She both served as a hospital ship and transport war cargo. For the latter part of 1944 and into 1945 she traveled from Singapore and Manila with a cargo of looted gold and other valuable Japanese conquests. The weeks before Japan surrender she arrived in Japan with gold, platinum, diamonds and gems. On August 15, 1945, the Japanese officially announce surrender. To cover up the war crimes and to hide the stolen loot, the ship was sunk on August 17, 1945, at [[Wakasa Bay]] in 400 feet of water. To sink her two 328 pound explosive charges were place in the bottom of the hull. To complete the hiding of the crime and the loot the crew that placed the bombs were killed on site. <ref>[http://ssmaritime.com/SS-Op-Ten-Noort.htm ssmaritime.com, Royal Netherlands Navy hospital ship ''Op ten Nothort'']</ref><ref>[http://www.netherlandsnavy.nl/Noort.htm Netherlands Navy ''Op ten Noort'']</ref> On 17 August 1945 the ship was scuttled at Wakasa Bay by placing explosive charges in the hull, to cover up the war crimes. <ref name=\"wrecksite.Hikawa Maru No.2\">{{cite web |year= 2011 |url = http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?59646|title = SS Hikawa Maru No.2 (+1945)| format = |publisher = wrecksite| accessdate = November 9, 2011 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"combinedfleet. Hikawa Maru 2\">{{cite web |year= 2010 |url = http://www.combinedfleet.com/Hikawa2_t.htm|title = IJN Hospital Ship HIKAWA MARU NO. 2 |publisher = combinedfleet.com | accessdate = November 9, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Post war==\nThe Netherlands thought the ''Op Ten Noort'' sank as the HMHS ''Tenno Maru HMHS'' near [[Makassar]] by a [[sea mine]]. Not knowing about the ''Hikawa Maru No.2'' plot.  In 1952 the ''Op Ten Noort'' was found after port area of Chinju Prefecture had a salvage investigations done. Professional diver from Kyoto, Mr. Shinta Koyua, photographed the wreck and it was identified as the lost ''Op Ten Noort''. In the 1953, the Dutch Government filed 700 million Yen claim against the Japan for compensation. After years of talks in the end 100 million Yen ($500,000) were paid to the Dutch Government in 1978. Info about the loot in the shipwreck is not public.\n\n==See also==\n*{{USS|Comfort|AH-6}}\n*{{USS|Hope|AH-7}}\n*[[AHS Centaur]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{August 1945 shipwrecks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anne Hutchinson}}\n[[Category:1927 ships]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in August 1945]]\n[[Category:Hospital ships| ]]\n[[Category:Japanese war crimes]]\n[[Category:Japanese hell ships]]\n", "text_old": "{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n| Ship image=File:S.S. Op ten Noort van de KPM, Bestanddeelnr 935-3124.jpg\n| Ship caption=SS Op Ten Noort as passenger ship\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n| Hide header=\n| Ship country= \n| Ship flag= {{NLD}}\n| Ship name=\n*SS ''Op Ten Noort'' \n* (after stolen: HMHS ''Tenno Maru'')\n*(Before sinking HMHS ''Hikawa Maru No.2'')\n| Ship namesake= \n*Up North \n* (Emperor Circle)\n*([[Hikawa Shrine (Saitama)|Hikawa Shrine, Saitama]])\n| Ship owner=[[Koninklijke Paketvaart-Maatschappij]]\n| Ship operator=\n*Koninklijke Paketvaart-Maatschappij\n*[[Royal Netherlands Navy]] \n*[[Imperial Japanese Navy]] \n| Ship registry=\n| Ship route=[[Dutch East Indies]]\n| Ship ordered=\n| Ship awarded=\n| Ship builder= [[Nederlandsche Scheepsbouw Maatschappij]]\n| Ship original cost=\n| Ship yard number=\n| Ship way number= \n| Ship laid down= \n| Ship launched= February 12, 1927  \n| Ship sponsor=\n| Ship christened=\n| Ship completed= November 9, 1927\n| Ship acquired=\n| Ship commissioned= February 14, 1942 as [[hospital ship]]\n| Ship decommissioned=\n| Ship in service=\n| Ship out of service=\n| Ship renamed=\n| Ship reclassified=\n| Ship refit=\n| Ship struck=\n| Ship reinstated=\n| Ship homeport=[[Java]]\n| Ship identification=PKEA\n| Ship motto=  \n| Ship nickname=\n| Ship honors=\n| Ship captured= February 21, 1941\n| Ship fate=17 August 1945 Scuttled at [[Wakasa Bay]] to cover up  [[Japanese war crimes|war crimes]]\n| Ship notes=\n| Ship badge=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n| Hide header=\n| Header caption=\n| Ship class=  \n| Ship tonnage=\n| Ship displacement={{convert|6076|LT|MT}}\n| Ship height=\n|Ship length={{Convert|129.5|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n|Ship beam={{Convert|16.8|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship draft= {{Convert|6.7|m|ftin|abbr=on}}\n| Ship depth=\n| Ship hold depth=\n| Ship decks=\n| Ship deck clearance=\n| Ship power=5 Coal boilers \n| Ship propulsion= \n*Two [[Hugo Lentz]] [[Reciprocating engine]]s [[Steam engine|steam]]\n*{{Convert|6000|hp|abbr=on}}\n*Two screws\n| Ship speed={{Convert|15|kn|lk=in}}\n| Ship range=\n| Ship endurance=\n| Ship boats=14 Life boats\n| Ship capacity=\n| Ship troops=\n| Ship complement=\n| Ship crew=162\n| Ship time to activate=\n| Ship sensors=\n| Ship EW=\n| Ship armament=none\n| Ship armor=none\n| Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n[[File:Mailboot SS Op ten Noord van de KPM in de haven van Tandjong Priok, Bestanddeelnr 934-8087.jpg|right|thumb|SS ''Op ten Noord'' in 1931 at [[Tanjung Priok]] in Indonesia, Dutch East Indies]]\n[[File:Het passagiersschip s.s. Op ten Noort van de Koninklijke Paketvaart Mij. (KPM), Bestanddeelnr 935-3116.jpg|right|thumb|SS ''Op ten Noort'' as passenger ship of [[Koninklijke Paketvaart-Maatschappij]] in the port of Surabaya Annotation in 1941]]\n[[File:StateLibQld 1 148207 Op Ten Noort (ship).jpg|right|thumb|SS ''Op ten Noort'']]\n\nThe '''SS ''Op ten Noort''''' was a luxury [[Passenger ship]] built by [[Nederlandsche Scheepsbouw Maatschappij]] in [[Amsterdam]], [[Netherlands]] and completed in 1927. The ship was built for and owned by [[Koninklijke Paketvaart-Maatschappij]] (Royal Packet Navigation Company). Op ten Noort means ''Up North''. In December of 1941 she became a [[Royal Netherlands Navy]] [[hospital ship]]. The [[Empire of Japan]] shortly after her conversion stole the ship and renamed her the '''HMHS ''Tenno Maru'''''. Before sinking her, she was renamed again to the '''HMHS ''Hikawa Maru No.2''''', after the [[Hikawa Shrine (Saitama)|Hikawa Shrine, Saitama]]. To cover up the [[Japanese war crimes|war crimes]] against the ship and her medical crew, at the end of the war, she was sunk on August 17, 1945.<ref>[http://ssmaritime.com/SS-Op-Ten-Noort-plan.htm SS ''Op ten Noort, plans]</ref> \n\n==Dutch East Indies==\nAs a luxury Passenger ship, the ''Op ten Noort'' was put to service in the what was called [[Dutch East Indies]], now [[Indonesia]]. Koninklijke Paketvaart Maatschappij headquarters were in [[Java]] at this time. ''Op ten Noort'' moved both passengers and [[cargo]] on the very profitable routes. On November 9, 1927 she had here [[List of maiden voyages|maid voyage]].  Her 1927 route was from [[Singapore]] to [[Bangkok]] to [[Saigon]] to [[Manila]] to [[Maluku Island]] to [[Bali]] to [[Jakarta]]. A few years the route changed to [[Java]] to [[Batavia, Dutch East Indies|Batavia]] to [[Muntok]] to [[Belawan]] to [[Deli Serdang Regency]]. ''Op ten Noort'' had a sister ship, the SS Plancius that operated in the [[South Pacific Ocean|South Pacific]] also. For fourteen years she serviced these towns as luxury ship. The 130 [[First class travel|First Class]] [[Cabin (ship)|cabins]] had access to lounges, bars, [[smoking room]] and a Tropical [[Verandah]]. For the very wealthy there were two Deluxe Suites with lounge, bedroom, two bathrooms, private deck (Veranda).  She had 18 [[Travel class|Second Class]] 18 cabins. They was for day passenger a [[Tweendeck]] and a [[cafeteria]].\n\n==World war 2==\nWith the outbreak of [[World war 2]] the SS ''Op Ten Noort'' was taken over by the Royal Dutch Navy in December of 1941 as she docked in Jakarta. There she was refit into a hospital ship. She was painted all white ship, with huge red crosses. The Dutch Government officially reported the [[Japanese Ministry of Foreign Affairs]] at the [[Swedish embassy]] in [[Tokyo]] of the change to SS ''Op Ten Noort''. She was now an operational hospital ship, as thus would not be part of the war effort, that is would not transport any weapons or active troops. On February 4, 1942 The Japanese Ministry of Foreign Affairs and [[Ministry of the Navy (Japan)|Naval Ministry]] acknowledges ''Op Ten Noort'' status change though the Swedish embassy. On February 21, 1941, completed she departed on her first trip to help wounded [[Allies of World War II|allies]]. But only a few hours out of port, the ''Op Ten Noort'' was bombed by the Empire of Japan in the [[Java Sea]]. One surgeon and three nurses were killed, eleven were badly wounded. Dutch Government sent a strong note of protest of the bombing to the Japan, through the Embassy of Sweden. After repairs, on 28 February 1942 she was commandeered by the [[Japanese destroyer Amatsukaze (1939)|Japanese destroyer Amatsukaze]] near [[Bawean Island]], stopping her rescue work again. Japanese forced her crew to transport their [[POW]]s to [[List of Japanese-run internment camps during World War II|Japan POW camps]]. The first POW move was that of 59 POWs from the [[USS Perch (SS-176)|USS ''Perch'']] that were on the [[Japanese destroyer Ushio (1930)|Japanese destroyer ''Ushi'']]. By the end of March 1942 she had 970 POWs, most from the 800 survivors from [[HMS Exeter (68)|HMS ''Exeter'']] that sank on March 1, 1942. The [[Prisoner of war|prisoners of war]] were kept in very poor conditions and feed only a cup of rice a day, called [[List of Japanese hell ships|Japanese hell ships]].  <ref>[https://www.britain-at-war.org.uk/WW2/Alf_King/html/japanese_pow.htm Japanese POW by Alf King]</ref> On 20 December 1942 she became the HMHS ''Tenno Maru'' an official Japanese Hospital Ship. The Dutch ship crew was taken off the ship and became POWs at Camp Myoshi, near [[Yokohama]]. Japan had signed the [[Hague Convention of 1907|Hague Convention X of 1907]] that stated attacking a hospital ship is a war crime.<ref name=\"hague10\">{{cite web |date= October 18, 1907|url = http://avalon.law.yale.edu/20th_century/hague10.asp|title = Convention for the adaptation to maritime war of the principles of the Geneva Convention|publisher = [[Yale University]]| accessdate = August 2, 2009 | last= |quote=}}</ref><ref>[https://archive.vn/20130616131847/http://www.minbuza.nl/en/key-topics/treaties/search-the-treaty-database/1899/7/002339.html Convention for the adaptation to maritime warfare of the principles of the Geneva Convention of 22 August 1864]</ref><ref>[http://www.combinedfleet.com/Hikawa2_t.htm combinedfleet.com ''Hikawa Maru No.2''] </ref>\n\nWith the war coming to an end, the ship was changed in October of 1944. A second dummy smokestack was added to \"hide her\". She was renamed the HMHS ''Hikawa Maru No.2''. She both served as a hospital ship and transport war cargo. For the latter part of 1944 and into 1945 she traveled from Singapore and Manila with a cargo of looted gold and other valuable Japanese conquests. The weeks before Japan surrender she arrived in Japan with gold, platinum, diamonds and gems. On August 15, 1945, the Japanese officially announce surrender. To cover up the war crimes and to hide the stolen loot, the ship was sunk on August 17, 1945, at [[Wakasa Bay]] in 400 feet of water. To sink her two 328 pound explosive charges were place in the bottom of the hull. To complete the hiding of the crime and the loot the crew that placed the bombs were killed on site. <ref>[http://ssmaritime.com/SS-Op-Ten-Noort.htm ssmaritime.com, Royal Netherlands Navy hospital ship ''Op ten Nothort'']</ref><ref>[http://www.netherlandsnavy.nl/Noort.htm Netherlands Navy ''Op ten Noort'']</ref> On 17 August 1945 the ship was scuttled at Wakasa Bay by placing explosive charges in the hull, to cover up the war crimes. <ref name=\"wrecksite.Hikawa Maru No.2\">{{cite web |year= 2011 |url = http://www.wrecksite.eu/wreck.aspx?59646|title = SS Hikawa Maru No.2 (+1945)| format = |publisher = wrecksite| accessdate = November 9, 2011 }}</ref>\n<ref name=\"combinedfleet. Hikawa Maru 2\">{{cite web |year= 2010 |url = http://www.combinedfleet.com/Hikawa2_t.htm|title = IJN Hospital Ship HIKAWA MARU NO. 2 |publisher = combinedfleet.com | accessdate = November 9, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Post war==\nThe Netherlands thought the ''Op Ten Noort'' sank as the HMHS ''Tenno Maru HMHS'' near [[Makassar]] by a [[sea mine]]. Not knowing about the ''Hikawa Maru No.2'' plot.  In 1952 the ''Op Ten Noort'' was found after port area of Chinju Prefecture had a salvage investigations done. Professional diver from Kyoto, Mr. Shinta Koyua, photographed the wreck and it was identified as the lost ''Op Ten Noort''. In the 1953, the Dutch Government filed 700 million Yen claim against the Japan for compensation. After years of talks in the end 100 million Yen ($500,000) were paid to the Dutch Government in 1978. Info about the loot in the shipwreck is not public.\n\n==See also==\n*{{USS|Comfort|AH-6}}\n*{{USS|Hope|AH-7}}\n*[[AHS Centaur]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{August 1945 shipwrecks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Anne Hutchinson}}\n[[Category:1927 ships]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in August 1945]]\n[[Category:Hospital ships| ]]\n[[Category:Japanese war crimes]]\n[[Category:Japanese hell ships]]\n", "name_user": "Telecineguy", "label": "safe", "comment": "sp", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SS_Op_Ten_Noort"}
{"title_page": "Cosmetic packaging", "text_new": "\n\n[[File:Red nail polish in application.jpg|right|thumb|Nail polish in a glass bottle with dispenser built into cap]]\n[[File:Lipstick in application.jpg|thumb|Lipstick in plastic disperser package]]\n[[File:\" 12 - ITALY - cosmetics of italian brands - Hair and skin care, scrub (gommage) shaving soap, body lotions and deodorant.JPG|thumb|Examples from Italy]]\n[[File:Cosmetic Packaging.png|thumb|200px|Examples of [[luxury packaging]]]]\n[[File:MODORobert.jpg|thumb|Jar for [[cold cream]] from the first half of the 20th century. From the [[Museo del Objeto del Objeto]] collection.]]\n\nThe term '''cosmetic packaging''' is used for cosmetic [[container]]s (primary packaging) and secondary packaging of [[Aroma compound|fragrances]] and [[cosmetics|cosmetic products]].<ref name=\"Cosper-Purposes-of-cosmetic-packaging\">{{cite web|last1=Cosper|first1=Alex|title=Purposes of Cosmetic Packaging|url=http://www.desjardin.fr/blog/purposes-of-cosmetic-packaging|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Turner-ISO22715\">{{cite web|last1=Cosper|first1=Alex|title=Cosmetic packaging compliant to ISO 22715|url=http://www.desjardin.fr/blog/cosmetic-packaging-compliant-to-iso-22715|publisher=Desjardin|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref> Cosmetic products are substances intended for human cleansing, beautifying and promoting an enhanced appearance without altering the body's structure or functions.<ref name=\"FDA-Cosmetics Definition\">{{cite web|title=Is It a Cosmetic, a Drug, or Both? (Or Is It Soap?)|url=https://www.fda.gov/Cosmetics/GuidanceRegulation/LawsRegulations/ucm074201.htm|publisher=U.S. Food & Drug Administration (FDA)|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nCosmetic packaging is standardized by an international norm set by the [[International Organization for Standardization]] and regulated by national or regional regulations such as those issued by the [[Regulation (European Union)|EU]] or the [[FDA]]. Marketers and manufacturers of cosmetic products must be compliant to these regulations to be able to market their cosmetic products in the corresponding [[Jurisdiction (area)|areas of jurisdiction]].<ref name=\"Turner-legally binding\">{{cite web|last1=Turner|first1=Dawn M.|title=Is the Standard ISO 22715 on Cosmetic Packaging legally binding?|url=http://www.desjardin.fr/blog/is-the-standard-iso-22715-on-cosmetic-packaging-legally-binding|publisher=Desjardin|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nA ''cosmetic container'', ''cosmetic box'', or ''cosmetic vessel'' is found in the historical records, both as an artifact, as [[relief]] items in some cultures, and are sometimes referenced in the historical or archaeological literature. They are sometimes created in specific styles, shapes, or motifs.\n\nThe named 'cosmetic vessel' in [[Ancient Greece]] is the [[pyxis (vessel)|pyxis]]. In [[Ancient Egypt]] artifacts of hieroglyphically inscribed kohl [[tube (fluid conveyance)|tube]]s are found; also [[kohl (cosmetics)|kohl]] vessels, and kohl spoons, which were formed in stylized shapes relevant to Egyptian ideology, including specific hieroglyphs.\n\nThe use of the ''cosmetic vessel'' may extend to trinket items, car-keys, toiletry accessories, for example, a nail clipper; as a non-toiletry storage container, it becomes an 'all-purpose' decorated, special-use vessel.\n\nContainers are known from many societies, ancient and modern. The [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]]s of the Americas made small containers woven from basketry materials, including pine needles.\n\n===Ancient Egypt===\nIn [[Ancient Egypt]] toiletry items began in the [[Predynastic Period]] with ivory cosmetic articles; also bone, stone, or pottery. Ivory combs, and [[kohl (cosmetics)|kohl]] spoons were among the first, with many shapes; common themes for shapes became the [[ankh]] symbol, ducks, lotus flowers, etc. In the time of the Predynastic and [[Old Kingdom]], bowls were also [[hand drill (hieroglyph)|mechanically drill]]ed, including miniature sizes, and were used in life and also included as [[grave goods]]. The bowls were either a type of unguent [[jar]], or a toiletry \"kohl cosmetic vessel\". The desert sun or [[Nile]] floodwaters during inundation produced a need for facial-eye protection, using 'eyepaint' or eyeliner when working in the flooded lands; theoretically, it was also used by males. The creation of predynastic [[cosmetic palette]]s with their eyepaint 'mixing circle', may have been the start of the lineage of the kohl cosmetic [[artifact (archaeology)|artifact]]s.  The famed [[Narmer Palette]], which scholars believe to commemorate the unification of upper and lower Egypt, is believed to be such a cosmetic article, perhaps even for the cosmetics of the king.<ref name=\"AHA-Palette of King Narmer\">{{cite web|title=Palette of King Narmer|url=https://www.historians.org/teaching-and-learning/teaching-resources/teaching-and-learning-in-the-digital-age/world-history/images-of-power-art-as-an-historiographic-tool/palette-of-king-narmer|publisher=American Historical Association|accessdate=17 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe term cosmetic packaging includes primary and secondary packaging. Primary packaging, also called cosmetic containers, is housing the cosmetic product. It is in direct contact with the cosmetic product. Secondary packaging is the outer wrapping of one or several cosmetic containers. An important difference between primary and secondary packaging is that any information that is necessary to clarify the safety of the product must appear on the primary package. Otherwise, much of the required information can appear on just the secondary packaging. \nThe cosmetic container shall carry the name of the [[distributor]], the [[ingredient]]s, define storage, nominal content, product identification (e.g., batch number), warning notices and directions for use.\nThe secondary packaging shall, in addition, carry the address of the distributor and information on the cosmetic's mode of action. The secondary packaging does not need to carry any product identification notice.\nIn cases where the cosmetic product is only wrapped by one single container, this container needs to carry all the information.<ref name=\"Cosper-PackagingFDA\">{{cite web|last1=Cosper|first1=Alex|title=What you should know when packaging cosmetics compliant to FDA regulations|url=http://www.desjardin.fr/blog/what-you-should-know-when-packaging-cosmetics-compliant-to-fda-regulations|publisher=Desjardin|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Purpose of cosmetic packaging==\nThere are multiple reasons why care must be put into cosmetic containers. Not only must they protect the product, but they also need to provide conveniences for vendors and ultimately consumers.\n\nThe main purpose of a cosmetic container is to [[cosmetic packaging#Protection|protect]] the product while it is in storage or being transported. The container must be a well thought out solution that protects the product from deterioration and helps preserve its quality. It must be an attractive looking container as part of the marketing of a beauty product.\n\nThe container must also contain [[cosmetic packaging#Labelling|labels]] that legibly display basic information about the product and the manufacturer. These labels include contact information, ingredients, expiration dates, warnings, and instructions. Labels not only identify products and their origins, but they also help provide consumers with the facts that cannot be confusing or misleading.\n\nIdeally, the container is made of durable material to give the product long shelf life. It must last even longer through consumer use. The frequent opening and closing of the container can take a toll on its condition over time. Ultimately, the container must protect the product to the degree that it remains a safe product for human consumption. In other words, the container must shield the product from dirt, dust, and germs.\n\nThe [[aesthetics]] of the container are considered extremely important since cosmetic products are mainly sold on [[cosmetic packaging#Creation of brand awareness|brand image]]. Since cosmetic products are not considered medicine or survival products, the marketing of cosmetics depends heavily on associating brand awareness with emotion. The container must convey [[emotion]]s about how the product will improve one's appearance and attitude. Many times cosmetics are repackaged and rebranded to help give them more market visibility.<ref name=\"Cosper-Purposes-of-cosmetic-packaging\" /><ref name=\"Cosper-Reasons-to-change\">{{cite web|last1=Cosper|first1=Alex|title=7 good Reasons to Change your Cosmetic Packaging|url=http://www.desjardin.fr/blog/7-good-reasons-to-change-your-cosmetic-packaging|publisher=Desjardin|accessdate=17 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"FDA: Fair Packaging and Labelling Act\">{{cite web|title=Regulatory Information: Fair Packaging and Labelling Act|url=https://www.fda.gov/RegulatoryInformation/Legislation/ucm148722.htm|publisher=FDA U.S. Food & Drug Administration|accessdate=17 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Protection===\nThe  main purpose of a container is to store the product so that it is not degraded through storage, shipping and handling.<ref name=\"Cosper-Purposes-of-cosmetic-packaging\" /> Degradation and damage can be caused by various causes. These causes can be categorized into [[Biological process|biological]], [[Chemical reaction|chemical]], [[temperature|thermal]] causes, damage caused by [[Radiation damage|radiation]] and damage caused by human interaction, by electric sources or by [[pressure]].<ref name=\"Cosper-PackagingFDA\" />\n\nIn addition to protecting the product, packaging also plays a big role [[marketing]] cosmetic products.<ref>{{Citation\n  | last = Shivsharan\n  | first = U S\n  | title = PACKAGING OF COSMETICS: A REVIEW\n  | publisher =   D.S.T.S. Mandal\u2019s college of pharmacy\n| year =2014\n  | pages =\n  | language = \n  | url = PackagingofcosmeticsAreview\n  | accessdate =3 December 2019\n}}</ref> While product quality is a major factor in the product's success, its packaging must be attractive since that's the essence of beauty marketing. Package design must capture the imagination and be associated with enhancing appearance. One of the keys to attractive packaging is the artistic use of colors. Most relevant for the marketer is the outer secondary packaging. However, there are cosmetics which are distributed in one single cosmetic container.<ref name=\"Cosper-Purposes-of-cosmetic-packaging\" />\n\n===Creation of brand awareness===\nCosmetic packages must not only convey [[beauty]], they must equate to [[brand awareness]]. Since the package is what the consumer initially sees, it is very influential in shaping perceptions about the product. Part of building brand awareness for a cosmetic product is associating it with [[emotion]]. Since it is not a survival product it is marketed to appeal to the desire to enhance appearance. The packaging must stimulate this emotion.<ref name=\"Cosper-Purposes-of-cosmetic-packaging\" />\n\n===Labelling===\n[[Label]]s tell consumers what they need to know about the product, as far as how to use it and where it comes from. Companies must list the ingredients and the function of the product, especially when it is unclear. The label must contain the contact information of the entity responsible for putting the product on the market. Labels also provide product tracking information.\n\nThe label must be easy to read, particularly for a customer where the product is being displayed. Certain compositions, such as perfumes, can be listed as one ingredient. Secondary packages are what the consumer sees as the outermost package. Primary packages are within the secondary package. Certain information can appear just on secondary packages. The most important information, particularly if the product is prone to misuse, must be displayed on both the primary and secondary packaging.<ref name=\"Turner-ISO22715\" /><ref name=\"CosmeticsEurope\">{{cite web|title=Understanding the label|url=https://www.cosmeticseurope.eu/cosmetic-products/understanding-label/|publisher=Cosmetics Europe Association|accessdate=3 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Information accuracy====\nOne of the most important aspects of regulations on labeling is that the information is accurate. Although the FDA does not have the resources to inspect all cosmetic products on the market, it can issue penalties for various violations involving packaging and labeling. It is the manufacturer's responsibility to make sure that its product is safe for public consumption.<ref name=\"Cosper-Purposes-of-cosmetic-packaging\" />\n\n====Avoidance of misleading information====\nNone of the information, including name and address, may be misleading. Words can be abbreviated only if it is clear what they represent. All text must be printed clearly on the packaging. Smaller packages in which text is too difficult to read should include tags with legible text.<ref name=\"Cosper-Purposes-of-cosmetic-packaging\" /><ref name=\"Turner-ISO22715\" />\n\n====Listing of ingredients====\nIngredients must be listed in a certain order with priority given to ingredients that represent 1% or more of the volume. These ingredients must be listed in descending order, based on weight. This group of ingredients is then followed by those that represent 1% or less of the product and listed in any order. Colorants may also be listed in any order.<ref name=\"Cosper-Purposes-of-cosmetic-packaging\" /><ref name=\"Turner-ISO22715\" />\n\n===Packaging in multiple layers===\nMany times cosmetic products are packaged in multiple layers. Whenever it is difficult to detect for the consumer, the number of units should be listed on the outer package, which should contain details about how to use the product and warnings on what to do if it is misused. It is essential that the product is protected from environmental elements such as [[mold]] and [[bacteria]].\n\nThe packaging must be sufficient enough to protect the mechanical, thermal, biological and chemical properties of the product. It should also be strong enough to withstand human tampering and [[radiation damage]].<ref name=\"Turner-ISO22715\" />\n\n==FDA and EU regulations==\nThe FDA oversees cosmetic packaging but does not test products. It leaves testing for safety up to manufacturers. It still provides regulations and can issue recalls when a product is associated with safety hazards. While the FDA does not have many restrictions on ingredients for cosmetic products, it does require that certain chemicals and colorants be listed.<ref name=\"Cosper-PackagingFDA\"/><ref name=\"FDA-CosmeticsLaw\">{{cite web|title=Cosmetics & U.S. Law |url=https://www.fda.gov/Cosmetics/GuidanceRegulation/LawsRegulations/ucm2005209.htm|publisher=U.S. Food & Drug Administration (FDA)|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs far as [[EU regulation]]s regarding packaging, manufacturers must be compliant with EC No. 1223/2009. One of these requirements involves the manufacturer issuing a safety report before putting the product on the market. The manufacturer must also disclose any serious undesirable effects (SUE) to the EU. Marketers are required to list nano-materials. \nThe EU's definition of \"ingredients\" does not include raw or technical materials used in products that do not end up in the final product. In some cases when durability is an issue, the manufacturer must list an expiration date after the product has been opened. The words \"best used before\" are common for identifying the product expiration date.<ref name=\"EU-Regulation-On-Cosmetics\">{{cite web|title=REGULATION (EC) No 1223/2009 OF THE EUROPEAN PARLIAMENT AND OF THE COUNCIL  of 30 November 2009  on cosmetic products|url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=celex:32009R1223|publisher=THE EUROPEAN PARLIAMENT AND THE COUNCIL OF THE EUROPEAN UNION|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Cosper-Packaging-in-EU\">{{cite web|last1=Cosper|first1=Alex|title=What you should know when packaging cosmetics compliant to EU regulations|url=http://www.desjardin.fr/blog/what-you-should-know-when-packaging-cosmetics-compliant-to-eu-regulations|publisher=Desjardin|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"CosmeticsEuropeRegulation\">{{cite web|title=Understanding the Cosmetics Regulation|url=https://www.cosmeticseurope.eu/cosmetics-industry/understanding-cosmetics-regulation/|publisher=Cosmetics Europe Association|accessdate=3 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==ISO-Standard==\nStandard [[ISO 22715]] provides specifications for the packaging and labeling of all cosmetic products that are sold or distributed at no charge; i.e. free samples. National regulations dictate what products are to be regarded as cosmetics. While ISO 22715 is not legally binding, national regulations regarding cosmetic products can be even stricter than those laid out in ISO 22715. The link between [[International standard|standards]] and [[regulation]]s is that a standard often represents the common denominator of [[national law]], as the [[standardization]] committee consists of members of most countries.<ref name=\"Turner-legally binding\" />\n\n==Standards and regulations==\n\nIn addition to cosmetic containers meeting the requirements of ISO, they must also comply with regulations set by the [[European Union]] and the [[United States]]. Cosmetics products marketed in the EU must comply with the [[Regulation (European Union)|EU-Regulation]] (EC) No. 1223/2009 of the European Parliament and of the Council on cosmetic products. The entity that puts the product on the market, known as the \"responsible person,\" must prepare a product safety report for the EU. [[Manufacturer]]s must notify the EU Cosmetic Products Notification Portal (CPNP) when they plan on putting products on the market. Some of the main EU requirements include identifying [[colorants]] and [[nanomaterial]]s and disclosing serious undesirable effects (SUE) to the EU.<ref name=\"EU-Regulation-On-Cosmetics\">{{cite web|title=REGULATION (EC) No 1223/2009 OF THE EUROPEAN PARLIAMENT AND OF THE COUNCIL  of 30 November 2009  on cosmetic products|url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=celex:32009R1223|publisher=THE EUROPEAN PARLIAMENT AND THE COUNCIL OF THE EUROPEAN UNION|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Cosper-Packaging-in-EU\">{{cite web|last1=Cosper|first1=Alex|title=What you should know when packaging cosmetics compliant to EU regulations|url=http://www.desjardin.fr/blog/what-you-should-know-when-packaging-cosmetics-compliant-to-eu-regulations|publisher=Desjardin|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"CosmeticsEuropeRegulation\">{{cite web|title=Understanding the Cosmetics Regulation|url=https://www.cosmeticseurope.eu/cosmetics-industry/understanding-cosmetics-regulation/|publisher=Cosmetics Europe Association|accessdate=3 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe main issue to remember about labels on cosmetic containers is that they provide safety guidance, including instructions for use and proper disposal. In the United States, companies must comply with the Federal Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act. Although the [[FDA]] does exercise authority over the cosmetic industry, it does not allocate sufficient resources to constantly monitor the industry. ISO defines an ingredient as a material that makes up the final product and not necessarily raw materials used in the production of the product. While the FDA does not have strict requirements for ingredients, they must still be listed on the primary container or secondary package.<ref name=\"FDA-CosmeticsLaw\">{{cite web|title=Cosmetics & U.S. Law |url=https://www.fda.gov/Cosmetics/GuidanceRegulation/LawsRegulations/ucm2005209.htm|publisher=U.S. Food & Drug Administration (FDA)|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Cosper:AboutFDA\">{{cite web|last1=Cosper|first1=Alex|title=What you should know when packaging cosmetics compliant to FDA regulations|url=http://www.desjardin.fr/blog/what-you-should-know-when-packaging-cosmetics-compliant-to-fda-regulations|publisher=Desjardin|accessdate=17 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Environmental Aspects==\n{{main article|sustainable packaging}}\nThe materials used for cosmetic containers concern for both protective and durable reasons. Containers must protect the product from environmental elements and should also move in the direction of eco-friendly solutions. In other words, the more the container can be recycled, the better for both the environment and cost-efficiency. Some of the factors that affect container durability include how the product substance responds to usage, chemical composition, and biology. It is essential that the container is able to withstand [[mold]] and [[mildew]], as well as [[contaminant]]s.\n\nThe container should be made of material resistant to hot or cold temperatures. It must also protect the product from ultraviolet rays, which could potentially harm the product. The container also cannot absorb the substances in the product. Traditionally, plastic materials or glass have been used for home cosmetics. Aluminum has become a popular type of container due to its lightweight yet sturdy quality, flexibility, durability, and recyclability. A key factor in what type of material can be used for containers is how compatible the material is with the product.<ref name=\"ASI-Sustainability\">{{cite web|title=Aluminium and Sustainability|url=http://aluminium-stewardship.org/about-asi/aluminium-and-sustainability/|publisher=Aluminium Stewardship Initiative|accessdate=17 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020061711/http://aluminium-stewardship.org/about-asi/aluminium-and-sustainability/|archive-date=20 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nPlastic packaging materials are controversially discussed because of their [[plastic pollution|polluting]] effects in particular to the marine environment. In 2014, a scientific study estimates the amount of floating [[Marine_pollution#Plastic_debris|plastics in the world's oceans]] to 5 trillion pieces with an accumulated weight of 250,000 tons.<ref name=\"Paper-PlasticPollution\">{{cite web|last1=Ericksen|first1=Marcus|last2=Lebreton|first2=Laurent|last3=Carson|first3=Henry|last4=Thiel|first4=Martin|last5=Moore|first5=Charles|last6=Borerro|first6=Jose|last7=Galgani|first7=Francois|title=Plastic Pollution in the World's Oceans: More than 5 Trillion Plastic Pieces Weighing over 250,000 Tons Afloat at Sea.|url=http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0111913|publisher=PLoS ONE|accessdate=17 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n\n==Examples==\n{{Commons category|Category:Archaeological cosmetic containers}}\n{{Commons category|Pyxides}}\n<gallery>\nFile:WoodenKohlTubeAmenhotepIII RosicrucianEgyptianMuseum.png|[[Kohl tube]], Ancient Egypt with hieroglyph inscription\nFile:AmarnaCosmeticJarDwarf MetropolitanMuseum.png|Egyptian kohl container & statuette\nFile:WLA nyhistorical Cosmetic Jar Taylors Saponaceous Compund.jpg|Recent historical round-type container, North America.\nFile:Desjardin-metal-tin-19th-century-Image2.jpg|19th century tin by [[Desjardin]] Metal Packaging\nFile:Black cosmetic plastic bottle.jpg|Plastic bottles and tubes\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n===Books===\n* Lockhart, H., and Paine, F.A.,  \"Packaging of Pharmaceuticals and Healthcare Products\", 1996, Blackie, {{ISBN|0-7514-0167-6}}\n* Yam, K.L., \"Encyclopedia of Packaging Technology\", John Wiley & Sons, 2009, {{ISBN|978-0-470-08704-6}}\n*Dayan. N, \"Formulating, Packaging, and Marketing of Natural Cosmetic Products\", 2011\n\n==External links==\n* [http://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=celex:32009R1223 www.http://eur-lex.europa.eu/cosmetics]\n* [https://www.fda.gov/Cosmetics/GuidanceRegulation/LawsRegulations/ucm2005209.htm https://www.fda.gov/Cosmetics/GuidanceRegulation]\n* [http://www.iso.org/iso/catalogue_detail.htm?csnumber=36436 www.iso.org/iso 22715:2006]\n{{packaging}}\n{{Cosmetics}}\n\n[[Category:Technical specifications]]\n[[Category:Perfumery]]\n[[Category:Cosmetics]]\n[[Category:Toiletry]]\n[[Category:Perfumes]]\n[[Category:Packaging]]\n[[Category:Cosmetic industry|Processes]]\n[[Category:Retail packaging]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n[[File:Red nail polish in application.jpg|right|thumb|Nail polish in glass bottle with dispenser built into cap]]\n[[File:Lipstick in application.jpg|thumb|Lipstick in plastic disperser package]]\n[[File:\" 12 - ITALY - cosmetics of italian brands - Hair and skin care, scrub (gommage) shaving soap, body lotions and deodorant.JPG|thumb|Examples from Italy]]\n[[File:Cosmetic Packaging.png|thumb|200px|Examples of [[luxury packaging]]]]\n[[File:MODORobert.jpg|thumb|Jar for [[cold cream]] from the first half of the 20th century. From the [[Museo del Objeto del Objeto]] collection.]]\n\nThe term '''cosmetic packaging''' is used for cosmetic [[container]]s (primary packaging) and secondary packaging of [[Aroma compound|fragrances]] and [[cosmetics|cosmetic products]].<ref name=\"Cosper-Purposes-of-cosmetic-packaging\">{{cite web|last1=Cosper|first1=Alex|title=Purposes of Cosmetic Packaging|url=http://www.desjardin.fr/blog/purposes-of-cosmetic-packaging|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Turner-ISO22715\">{{cite web|last1=Cosper|first1=Alex|title=Cosmetic packaging compliant to ISO 22715|url=http://www.desjardin.fr/blog/cosmetic-packaging-compliant-to-iso-22715|publisher=Desjardin|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref> Cosmetic products are substances intended for human cleansing, beautifying and promoting an enhanced appearance without altering the body's structure or functions.<ref name=\"FDA-Cosmetics Definition\">{{cite web|title=Is It a Cosmetic, a Drug, or Both? (Or Is It Soap?)|url=https://www.fda.gov/Cosmetics/GuidanceRegulation/LawsRegulations/ucm074201.htm|publisher=U.S. Food & Drug Administration (FDA)|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nCosmetic packaging is standardized by an international norm set by the [[International Organization for Standardization]] and regulated by national or regional regulations such as those issued by the [[Regulation (European Union)|EU]] or the [[FDA]]. Marketers and manufacturers of cosmetic products must be compliant to these regulations to be able to market their cosmetic products in the corresponding [[Jurisdiction (area)|areas of jurisdiction]].<ref name=\"Turner-legally binding\">{{cite web|last1=Turner|first1=Dawn M.|title=Is the Standard ISO 22715 on Cosmetic Packaging legally binding?|url=http://www.desjardin.fr/blog/is-the-standard-iso-22715-on-cosmetic-packaging-legally-binding|publisher=Desjardin|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\nA ''cosmetic container'', ''cosmetic box'', or ''cosmetic vessel'' is found in the historical records, both as an artifact, as [[relief]] items in some cultures, and are sometimes referenced in historical or archaeological literature. They are sometimes created in specific styles, shapes, or motifs.\n\nThe named 'cosmetic vessel' in [[Ancient Greece]] is the [[pyxis (vessel)|pyxis]]. In [[Ancient Egypt]] artifacts of hieroglyphically inscribed kohl [[tube (fluid conveyance)|tube]]s are found; also [[kohl (cosmetics)|kohl]] vessels, and kohl spoons, which were formed in stylized shapes relevant to Egyptian ideology, including specific hieroglyphs.\n\nThe use of the ''cosmetic vessel'' may extend to trinket items, car-keys, toiletry accessories, for example a nail clipper; as a non-toiletry storage container, it becomes an 'all-purpose' decorated, special-use vessel.\n\nContainers are known from many societies, ancient and modern. The [[Indigenous peoples of the Americas|Native American]]s of the Americas made small containers woven from basketry materials, including pine needles.\n\n===Ancient Egypt===\nIn [[Ancient Egypt]] toiletry items began in the [[Predynastic Period]] with ivory cosmetic articles; also bone, stone, or pottery. Ivory combs, and [[kohl (cosmetics)|kohl]] spoons were among the first, with many shapes; common themes for shapes became the [[ankh]] symbol, ducks, lotus flowers, etc. In the time of the Predynastic and [[Old Kingdom]], bowls were also [[hand drill (hieroglyph)|mechanically drill]]ed, including miniature sizes, and were used in life and also included as [[grave goods]]. The bowls were either a type of unguent [[jar]], or a toiletry \"kohl cosmetic vessel\". The desert sun or [[Nile]] floodwaters during inundation produced a need for facial-eye protection, using 'eyepaint' or eyeliner, when working in the flooded lands; theoretically it was also used by males. The creation of predynastic [[cosmetic palette]]s with their eyepaint 'mixing circle', may have been the start of the lineage of the kohl cosmetic [[artifact (archaeology)|artifact]]s.  The famed [[Narmer Palette]], which scholars believe to commemorate the unification of upper and lower Egypt, is believed to be such a cosmetic article, perhaps even for the cosmetics of the king.<ref name=\"AHA-Palette of King Narmer\">{{cite web|title=Palette of King Narmer|url=https://www.historians.org/teaching-and-learning/teaching-resources/teaching-and-learning-in-the-digital-age/world-history/images-of-power-art-as-an-historiographic-tool/palette-of-king-narmer|publisher=American Historical Association|accessdate=17 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe term cosmetic packaging includes primary and the secondary packaging. Primary packaging, also called cosmetic container, is housing the cosmetic product. It is in direct contact with the cosmetic product. Secondary packaging is the outer wrapping of one or several cosmetic containers. An important difference between primary and secondary packaging is that any information that is necessary to clarify the safety of the product must appear on the primary package. Otherwise, much of the required information can appear on just the secondary packaging. \nThe cosmetic container shall carry the name of the [[distributor]], the [[ingredient]]s, define storage, nominal content, product identification (e.g., batch number), warning notices and directions for use.\nThe secondary packaging shall, in addition, carry the address of the distributor and information on the cosmetic's mode of action. The secondary packaging does not need to carry any product identification notice.\nIn cases where the cosmetic product is only wrapped by one single container, this container needs to carry all the information.<ref name=\"Cosper-PackagingFDA\">{{cite web|last1=Cosper|first1=Alex|title=What you should know when packaging cosmetics compliant to FDA regulations|url=http://www.desjardin.fr/blog/what-you-should-know-when-packaging-cosmetics-compliant-to-fda-regulations|publisher=Desjardin|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Purpose of cosmetic packaging==\nThere are multiple reasons why care must be put into cosmetic containers. Not only must they protect the product, they need to provide conveniences for vendors and ultimately consumers.\n\nThe main purpose of a cosmetic container is to [[cosmetic packaging#Protection|protect]] the product while it is in storage or being transported. The container must be a well thought out solution that protects the product from deterioration and helps preserve its quality. It must be an attractive looking container as part of the marketing of a beauty product.\n\nThe container must also contain [[cosmetic packaging#Labelling|labels]] that legibly display basic information about the product and the manufacturer. These labels include contact information, ingredients, expiration dates, warnings and instructions. Labels not only identify products and their origins, they help provide consumers with the facts that cannot be confusing or misleading.\n\nIdeally, the container is made of durable material to give the product a long shelf life. It must last even longer through consumer use. The frequent opening and closing of the container can take a toll on its condition over time. Ultimately, the container must protect the product to the degree that it remains a safe product for human consumption. In other words, the container must shield the product from dirt, dust and germs.\n\nThe [[aesthetics]] of the container are considered extremely important since cosmetic products are mainly sold on [[cosmetic packaging#Creation of brand awareness|brand image]]. Since cosmetic products are not considered medicine or survival products, the marketing of cosmetics depends heavily on associating brand awareness with emotion. The container must convey [[emotion]]s about how the product will improve one's appearance and attitude. Many times cosmetics are repackaged and rebranded to help give them more market visibility.<ref name=\"Cosper-Purposes-of-cosmetic-packaging\" /><ref name=\"Cosper-Reasons-to-change\">{{cite web|last1=Cosper|first1=Alex|title=7 good Reasons to Change your Cosmetic Packaging|url=http://www.desjardin.fr/blog/7-good-reasons-to-change-your-cosmetic-packaging|publisher=Desjardin|accessdate=17 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"FDA: Fair Packaging and Labelling Act\">{{cite web|title=Regulatory Information: Fair Packaging and Labelling Act|url=https://www.fda.gov/RegulatoryInformation/Legislation/ucm148722.htm|publisher=FDA U.S. Food & Drug Administration|accessdate=17 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Protection===\nThe  main purpose of a container is to store the product so that it is not degraded through storage, shipping and handling.<ref name=\"Cosper-Purposes-of-cosmetic-packaging\" /> Degradation and damage can be caused by various causes. These causes can be categorized into [[Biological process|biological]], [[Chemical reaction|chemical]], [[temperature|thermal]] causes, damage caused by [[Radiation damage|radiation]] and damage caused by human interaction, by electric sources or by [[pressure]].<ref name=\"Cosper-PackagingFDA\" />\n\nIn addition to protecting the product, packaging also plays a big role [[marketing]] cosmetic products.<ref>{{Citation\n  | last = Shivsharan\n  | first = U S\n  | title = PACKAGING OF COSMETICS: A REVIEW\n  | publisher =   D.S.T.S. Mandal\u2019s college of pharmacy\n| year =2014\n  | pages =\n  | language = \n  | url = PackagingofcosmeticsAreview\n  | accessdate =3 December 2019\n}}</ref> While product quality is a major factor in the product's success, its packaging must be attractive since that's the essence of beauty marketing. Package design must capture the imagination and be associated with enhancing appearance. One of the keys to attractive packaging is artistic use of colors. Most relevant for the marketer is the outer secondary packaging. However, there are cosmetics which are distributed in one single cosmetic container.<ref name=\"Cosper-Purposes-of-cosmetic-packaging\" />\n\n===Creation of brand awareness===\nCosmetic packages must not only convey [[beauty]], they must equate to [[brand awareness]]. Since the package is what the consumer initially sees, it is very influential in shaping perceptions about the product. Part of building brand awareness for a cosmetic product is associating it with [[emotion]]. Since it is not a survival product it is marketed to appeal to the desire to enhance appearance. The packaging must stimulate this emotion.<ref name=\"Cosper-Purposes-of-cosmetic-packaging\" />\n\n===Labelling===\n[[Label]]s tell consumers what they need to know about the product, as far as how to use it and where it comes from. Companies must list the ingredients and the function of the product, especially when it is unclear. The label must contain contact information of the entity responsible for putting the product on the market. Labels also provide product tracking information.\n\nThe label must be easy to read, particularly for a customer where the product is being displayed. Certain compositions, such as perfumes, can be listed as one ingredient. Secondary packages are what the consumer sees as the outermost package. Primary packages are within the secondary package. Certain information can appear just on secondary packages. The most important information, particularly if the product is prone to misuse, must be displayed on both the primary and secondary packaging.<ref name=\"Turner-ISO22715\" /><ref name=\"CosmeticsEurope\">{{cite web|title=Understanding the label|url=https://www.cosmeticseurope.eu/cosmetic-products/understanding-label/|publisher=Cosmetics Europe Association|accessdate=3 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Information accuracy====\nOne of the most important aspects of regulations on labelling is that the information is accurate. Although the FDA does not have the resources to inspect all cosmetic products on the market, it can issue penalties for various violations involving packaging and labelling. It is the manufacturer's responsibility to make sure that its product is safe for public consumption.<ref name=\"Cosper-Purposes-of-cosmetic-packaging\" />\n\n====Avoidance of misleading information====\nNone of the information, including name and address, may be misleading. Words can be abbreviated only if it is clear what they represent. All text must be printed clearly on the packaging. Smaller packages in which text is too difficult to read, should include tags with legible text.<ref name=\"Cosper-Purposes-of-cosmetic-packaging\" /><ref name=\"Turner-ISO22715\" />\n\n====Listing of ingredients====\nIngredients must be listed in a certain order with priority given to ingredients that represent 1% or more of the volume. These ingredients must be listed in descending order, based on weight. This group of ingredients is then followed by those that represent 1% or less of the product and listed in any order. Colorants may also be listed in any order.<ref name=\"Cosper-Purposes-of-cosmetic-packaging\" /><ref name=\"Turner-ISO22715\" />\n\n===Packaging in multiple layers===\nMany times cosmetic products are packaged in multiple layers. Whenever it is difficult to detect for the consumer, the number of units should be listed on the outer package, which should contain details about how to use the product and warnings on what to do if it is misused. It is essential that the product is protected from environmental elements such as [[mould]] and [[bacteria]].\n\nThe packaging must be sufficient enough to protect the mechanical, thermal, biological and chemical properties of the product. It should also be strong enough to withstand human tampering and [[radiation damage]].<ref name=\"Turner-ISO22715\" />\n\n==FDA and EU regulations==\nThe FDA oversees cosmetic packaging but does not test products. It leaves testing for safety up to manufacturers. It still provides regulations and can issue recalls when a product is associated with safety hazards. While the FDA does not have many restrictions on ingredients for cosmetic products, it does require that certain chemicals and colorants be listed.<ref name=\"Cosper-PackagingFDA\"/><ref name=\"FDA-CosmeticsLaw\">{{cite web|title=Cosmetics & U.S. Law |url=https://www.fda.gov/Cosmetics/GuidanceRegulation/LawsRegulations/ucm2005209.htm|publisher=U.S. Food & Drug Administration (FDA)|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs far as [[EU regulation]]s regarding packaging, manufacturers must be compliant with EC No. 1223/2009. One of these requirements involves the manufacturer issuing a safety report before putting the product on the market. The manufacturer must also disclose any serious undesirable effects (SUE) to the EU. Marketers are required to list nano-materials. \nThe EU's definition of \"ingredients\" does not include raw or technical materials used in production that do not end up in the final product. In some cases when durability is an issue, the manufacturer must list an expiration date after the product has been opened. The words \"best used before\" are common for identifying the product expiration date.<ref name=\"EU-Regulation-On-Cosmetics\">{{cite web|title=REGULATION (EC) No 1223/2009 OF THE EUROPEAN PARLIAMENT AND OF THE COUNCIL  of 30 November 2009  on cosmetic products|url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=celex:32009R1223|publisher=THE EUROPEAN PARLIAMENT AND THE COUNCIL OF THE EUROPEAN UNION|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Cosper-Packaging-in-EU\">{{cite web|last1=Cosper|first1=Alex|title=What you should know when packaging cosmetics compliant to EU regulations|url=http://www.desjardin.fr/blog/what-you-should-know-when-packaging-cosmetics-compliant-to-eu-regulations|publisher=Desjardin|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"CosmeticsEuropeRegulation\">{{cite web|title=Understanding the Cosmetics Regulation|url=https://www.cosmeticseurope.eu/cosmetics-industry/understanding-cosmetics-regulation/|publisher=Cosmetics Europe Association|accessdate=3 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==ISO-Standard==\nStandard [[ISO 22715]] provides specifications for the packaging and labeling of all cosmetic products that are sold or distributed at no charge; i.e. free samples. National regulations dictate what products are to be regarded as cosmetics. While ISO 22715 is not legally binding, national regulations regarding cosmetic products can be even stricter than those laid out in ISO 22715. The link between [[International standard|standards]] and [[regulation]]s is that a standard often represents the common denominator of [[national law]], as the [[standardization]] committee consists of members of most countries.<ref name=\"Turner-legally binding\" />\n\n==Standards and regulations==\n\nIn addition to cosmetic containers meeting the requirements of ISO, they must also comply with regulations set by the [[European Union]] and the [[United States]]. Cosmetics products marketed in the EU must comply with the [[Regulation (European Union)|EU-Regulation]] (EC) No. 1223/2009 of the European Parliament and of the Council on cosmetic products. The entity that puts the product on the market, known as the \"responsible person,\" must prepare a product safety report for the EU. [[Manufacturer]]s must notify the EU Cosmetic Products Notification Portal (CPNP) when they plan on putting products on the market. Some of the main EU requirements include identifying [[colorants]] and [[nanomaterial]]s and disclosing serious undesirable effects (SUE) to the EU.<ref name=\"EU-Regulation-On-Cosmetics\">{{cite web|title=REGULATION (EC) No 1223/2009 OF THE EUROPEAN PARLIAMENT AND OF THE COUNCIL  of 30 November 2009  on cosmetic products|url=http://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=celex:32009R1223|publisher=THE EUROPEAN PARLIAMENT AND THE COUNCIL OF THE EUROPEAN UNION|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Cosper-Packaging-in-EU\">{{cite web|last1=Cosper|first1=Alex|title=What you should know when packaging cosmetics compliant to EU regulations|url=http://www.desjardin.fr/blog/what-you-should-know-when-packaging-cosmetics-compliant-to-eu-regulations|publisher=Desjardin|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"CosmeticsEuropeRegulation\">{{cite web|title=Understanding the Cosmetics Regulation|url=https://www.cosmeticseurope.eu/cosmetics-industry/understanding-cosmetics-regulation/|publisher=Cosmetics Europe Association|accessdate=3 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nThe main issues to remember about labels on cosmetic containers is that they provide safety guidance, including instructions for use and proper disposal. In the United States, companies must comply with the Federal Food, Drug and Cosmetic Act. Although the [[FDA]] does exercise authority over the cosmetic industry, it does not allocate sufficient resources to constantly monitor the industry. ISO defines an ingredient as a material that makes up the final product and not necessarily raw materials used in the production of the product. While the FDA does not have strict requirements for ingredients, they must still be listed on the primary container or secondary package.<ref name=\"FDA-CosmeticsLaw\">{{cite web|title=Cosmetics & U.S. Law |url=https://www.fda.gov/Cosmetics/GuidanceRegulation/LawsRegulations/ucm2005209.htm|publisher=U.S. Food & Drug Administration (FDA)|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Cosper:AboutFDA\">{{cite web|last1=Cosper|first1=Alex|title=What you should know when packaging cosmetics compliant to FDA regulations|url=http://www.desjardin.fr/blog/what-you-should-know-when-packaging-cosmetics-compliant-to-fda-regulations|publisher=Desjardin|accessdate=17 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Environmental Aspects==\n{{main article|sustainable packaging}}\nThe materials used for cosmetic containers are of concern for both protective and sustainable reasons. The container must protect the product from environmental elements and it must also move in the direction of eco-friendly solutions. In other words, the more the container can be recycled, the better for both the environment and cost efficiency. Some of the factors that affect container durability include how the product substance responds to usage, chemical composition and biology. It is essential that the container is able to withstand [[mold]] and [[mildew]], as well as [[contaminant]]s.\n\nThe container must be made of materials resistant to hot or cold temperatures. It must also protect the product from ultraviolet rays, which can potentially damage the product. The container also cannot absorb product substances. Traditionally, plastic material or glass have been used to house cosmetics. Aluminum has become a popular type of container due to its lightweight yet sturdy quality, flexibility, durability and recyclability. A key factor in what type of material can be used for containers is how compatible the material is with the product.<ref name=\"ASI-Sustainability\">{{cite web|title=Aluminium and Sustainability|url=http://aluminium-stewardship.org/about-asi/aluminium-and-sustainability/|publisher=Aluminium Stewardship Initiative|accessdate=17 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161020061711/http://aluminium-stewardship.org/about-asi/aluminium-and-sustainability/|archive-date=20 October 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nPlastic packaging materials are controversially discussed because of their [[plastic pollution|polluting]] effects in particular to the marine environment. In 2014, a scientific study estimates the amount of floating [[Marine_pollution#Plastic_debris|plastics in the world's oceans]] to 5 trillion pieces with an accumulated weight of 250,000 tons.<ref name=\"Paper-PlasticPollution\">{{cite web|last1=Ericksen|first1=Marcus|last2=Lebreton|first2=Laurent|last3=Carson|first3=Henry|last4=Thiel|first4=Martin|last5=Moore|first5=Charles|last6=Borerro|first6=Jose|last7=Galgani|first7=Francois|title=Plastic Pollution in the World's Oceans: More than 5 Trillion Plastic Pieces Weighing over 250,000 Tons Afloat at Sea.|url=http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0111913|publisher=PLoS ONE|accessdate=17 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n\n==Examples==\n{{Commons category|Category:Archaeological cosmetic containers}}\n{{Commons category|Pyxides}}\n<gallery>\nFile:WoodenKohlTubeAmenhotepIII RosicrucianEgyptianMuseum.png|[[Kohl tube]], Ancient Egypt with hieroglyph inscription\nFile:AmarnaCosmeticJarDwarf MetropolitanMuseum.png|Egyptian kohl container & statuette\nFile:WLA nyhistorical Cosmetic Jar Taylors Saponaceous Compund.jpg|Recent historical round-type container, North America.\nFile:Desjardin-metal-tin-19th-century-Image2.jpg|19th century tin by [[Desjardin]] Metal Packaging\nFile:Black cosmetic plastic bottle.jpg|Plastic bottles and tubes\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n\n===Books===\n* Lockhart, H., and Paine, F.A.,  \"Packaging of Pharmaceuticals and Healthcare Products\", 1996, Blackie, {{ISBN|0-7514-0167-6}}\n* Yam, K.L., \"Encyclopedia of Packaging Technology\", John Wiley & Sons, 2009, {{ISBN|978-0-470-08704-6}}\n*Dayan. N, \"Formulating, Packaging, and Marketing of Natural Cosmetic Products\", 2011\n\n==External links==\n* [http://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/?uri=celex:32009R1223 www.http://eur-lex.europa.eu/cosmetics]\n* [https://www.fda.gov/Cosmetics/GuidanceRegulation/LawsRegulations/ucm2005209.htm https://www.fda.gov/Cosmetics/GuidanceRegulation]\n* [http://www.iso.org/iso/catalogue_detail.htm?csnumber=36436 www.iso.org/iso 22715:2006]\n{{packaging}}\n{{Cosmetics}}\n\n[[Category:Technical specifications]]\n[[Category:Perfumery]]\n[[Category:Cosmetics]]\n[[Category:Toiletry]]\n[[Category:Perfumes]]\n[[Category:Packaging]]\n[[Category:Cosmetic industry|Processes]]\n[[Category:Retail packaging]]\n", "name_user": "Ravitavethiya", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cosmetic_packaging"}
{"title_page": "Michael Smiley", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=March 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Michael Smiley\n| image        = Michael Smiley (cropped).jpg\n| caption      = Smiley in 2016\n| birth_date   = {{birth year and age|1963}}\n| birth_place  = [[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]]\n| occupation   = [[Comedian]] & [[Actor]]\n| spouse       = [[Miranda Sawyer]]\n| children     = 1\n}}\n\n'''Michael Smiley''' (born 1963) is a [[People of Northern Ireland|Northern Irish]] comedian and actor. He is perhaps best known for his roles in the films ''[[Kill List]]'' (2011) and ''[[The Lobster]]'' (2015).\n\n==Early life==\nSmiley was born in 1963 in [[Belfast]] and grew up in [[Holywood]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01qb0qx/profiles/michael-smiley |title=BBC One - Monumental - Michael Simley |publisher=[[BBC One]] |accessdate=18 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/film-tv/news/michael-smiley-im-an-overnight-success-after-20-years-30202335.html|title=Michael Smiley: 'I'm an overnight success after 20 years!'|author=<!-- Staff -->|work=[[Belfast Telegraph]]|date=21 April 2014|accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref> He moved to [[London]] in his 20s with his wife. He began doing stand-up in 1993, after accepting a bet at an [[open mike|open-mic night]]. He had worked as a [[Bicycle messenger|cycle courier]] (like his character in ''[[Spaced]]'') and as an [[acid house]] [[Disc jockey|DJ]].<ref name=\"EdinburghFestival\">{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/edinburgh_festival/146739.stm |title=Living the life of Smiley |date=10 August 1998 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=18 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHe became well known for his role as [[Tyres O'Flaherty]], the bicycle riding raver, in two episodes of the [[Channel 4]] sitcom ''Spaced'', and for his appearances at the [[Edinburgh Fringe]] and the [[Melbourne Comedy Festival]].<ref name=\"EdinburghFestival\"/> He played Mac, a former member of the [[British Army]]'s [[Parachute Regiment (United Kingdom)|Parachute Regiment]] in the 2008 horror film ''[[Outpost (2008 film)|Outpost]]'' and as a zombie in ''[[Shaun of the Dead]]''.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\nIn 2003, he guest starred in the ''[[Doctor Who]]'' audio drama ''[[Creatures of Beauty]]''. In 2004 he appeared in season 2, episode 4 of ''[[Hustle (TV series)|Hustle]]'' as Max the forger.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/tv-programme/e/dvf7q/hustle--s2-e4-missions|title=Hustle - what time is it on TV? Episode 4 Series 2 cast list and preview|website=RadioTimes|access-date=10 September 2016}}</ref> He also was a small character in episode 2 \"The Model\" of ''[[15 Storeys High]]''.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\nHe has appeared in all three series of ''[[The Maltby Collection]]'' on Radio 4 as Des Wainwright, an eccentric security guard who keeps repeating himself and reminding people he was in the [[Special Air Service|SAS]]. He plays the part of Benny \"Deadhead\" Silver in the BBC drama series ''[[Luther (TV series)|Luther]]''. In 2010, he had a major role in the film ''[[Burke and Hare (2010 film)|Burke & Hare]]'' alongside his ''Spaced'' co-stars [[Simon Pegg]] and [[Jessica Hynes]].\n\nIn 2011, he starred in British horror film ''[[Kill List]]''. The film received critical acclaim, and earned him the [[BIFA Award for Best Supporting Actor|\"Best Supporting Actor\" Award]] at the [[British Independent Film Awards 2011|2011 British Independent Film Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.holymoly.com/film-dvd/pictures/british-independent-film-awards-2011-fassbender-ramsey-sophie-peep-show-win60714|title=British Independent Film Awards 2011: Fassbender, Ramsey & Sophie from Peep Show win|last=Exley|first=Gemma|date=5 December 2012|website=[[Holy Moly]]|accessdate=18 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103231328/http://www.holymoly.com/film-dvd/pictures/british-independent-film-awards-2011-fassbender-ramsey-sophie-peep-show-win60714|archivedate=3 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, he has appeared in an episode of [[BBC One]]'s ''[[Ripper Street]]'' as [[George Lusk]], and the critically acclaimed [[Channel 4]] shows ''[[Utopia (UK TV series)|Utopia]]'' as Detective Reynolds and ''[[Black Mirror]]'' as Baxter.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} He also starred in ''[[A Field in England]]'' as the main antagonist, the alchemist O'Neill. He also played Roddy in ''[[Father Figure (TV series)|Father Figure]]''. In November 2013 he appeared in the third episode of the [[BBC Two]] [[Mitchell and Webb]] comedy ''[[Ambassadors (TV series)|Ambassadors]]'' as Mr Jackson. In 2014, he played Micky Murray in [[BBC Four]]'s ''[[The Life of Rock with Brian Pern]]''.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\nTo coincide with the [[2014 Giro d'Italia, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 1|opening stages]] of the [[Giro d'Italia]] in May 2014, ''Michael Smiley:Something to Ride Home About'' was a [[travelog]] programme for [[BBC Northern Ireland]], directed by [[George Kane (director)|George Kane]], featuring Smiley cycling around Northern Ireland and meeting local people.<ref name=\"ride\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&aid=73&force=1&only=1&rid=4287457&tpl=archnews|title=\u2018Michael Smiley: Something To Ride Home About\u2019 Gets Second Series|publisher=[[Irish Film and Television Network]]|date=18 August 2014|accessdate=22 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"IrishmanAbroadMS\">{{cite podcast|authorlink=Jarlath Regan|author=Jarlath Regan|edition=7|work=[[An Irishman Abroad]]|title=Michael Smiley|publisher=[[SoundCloud]]|date=14 October 2013|url=https://soundcloud.com/an-irishman-abroad/george-kane-episode-56|accessdate=28 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141215070425/https://soundcloud.com/an-irishman-abroad/george-kane-episode-56|archivedate=15 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"IrishmanAbroadGK\">{{cite podcast|authorlink=Jarlath Regan|author=Jarlath Regan|edition=56|work=[[An Irishman Abroad]]|title=George Kane|publisher=[[SoundCloud]]|date=11 June 2014|url=https://soundcloud.com/an-irishman-abroad/george-kane-episode-56|accessdate=28 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141215070425/https://soundcloud.com/an-irishman-abroad/george-kane-episode-56|archivedate=15 December 2014}}</ref> A second series has been commissioned for 2015.<ref name=\"ride\"/>\n\nIn 2014 Smiley played Colonel Morgan Blue in the ''[[Doctor Who]]'' episode \"[[Into the Dalek]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Mulkern|first=Patrick|date=30 August 2014|title=Into the Dalek ****|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/blog/2014-08-30/into-the-dalek|newspaper=[[Radio Times]]|location=London, UK|accessdate=30 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Smiley also starred in the Netflix show ''[[Black Mirror]]'' as Baxter in \u201c[[White Bear (Black Mirror)|White Bear]]\u201d. He also had a major role in British crime seri''es [[Luther (TV series)]]'' acting as \u201cDeadhead\u201d [[Benny Silver]] from 2010 until 2019.\n\nIn 2019, Smiley co-starred with [[Elijah Wood]] and [[Martin Donovan]] in the film ''[[Come to Daddy (film)|Come to Daddy]]'' directed by [[Ant Timpson]].<ref>[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/come-daddy-1277024 Come to Daddy Review] by Frank Scheck, The Hollywood Reporter, February 6, 2020.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSmiley is married to journalist/broadcaster [[Miranda Sawyer]], with whom he has a son and a daughter. The family lives near Brockwell Park in [[Herne Hill]], [[London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.notabaddad.com/2013/06/miranda-sawyer-interview|title=Miranda Sawyer Interview|last=Tyler|first=Simon|date=7 June 2013|website=Not a Bad Dad|accessdate=18 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928184832/http://www.notabaddad.com/2013/06/miranda-sawyer-interview/|archive-date=28 September 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> He shared a flat with [[Simon Pegg]] and [[Nick Frost]] in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/9103419.welcome-to-the-bonkers-world-of-michael-smiley/|title=Welcome to the bonkers world of Michael Smiley|last=Marsh|first=Hannah|date=|newspaper=[[The Echo (Essex)|The Echo]]|accessdate=18 August 2013|location=[[Basildon]]}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography ==\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1989 || ''[[The Heist (1989 film)|The Heist]]'' || Detective || Television film; uncredited\n|-\n| 2000 || ''[[Burnside (TV series)|Burnside]]'' || Matthew Hutchins || Episode: \"Back with a Vengeance: Part 1\"\n|-\n| 1999-2001 || ''[[Spaced]]'' || [[Tyres O'Flaherty]] || 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2000-2002 || ''[[Time Gentlemen Please]]'' || Martin || 3 episodes\n|-\n| 2002 || ''[[15 Storeys High]]'' || Insistent Irish visitor || Episode: \"The Model\"\n|-\n| 2004 || ''[[Murder Prevention]]'' || DC Maurice Gibney || 4 episodes\n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[Bleak House]]'' || Phil Squod || 8 episodes\n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[Hustle (TV series)|Hustle]]'' || Max || Episode: \"Missions\"\n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[ShakespeaRe-Told]]'' || Peter || Episode: \"[[Much Ado About Nothing]]\"\n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[Rose and Maloney]]'' || DS Mallam || Episode: \"Rise & Fall\"\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[In the Spider's Web]]'' || Phil || Television film\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[Y Pris]]'' || Captain || Episode: \"Episode #1.3\"\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[Nearly Famous]]'' || Danny || Episode: \"Episode #1.5\"\n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[The Wrong Door]]'' || || 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[HolbyBlue]]'' || Brendan Duffy || Episode: \"Episode #2.10\"\n|-\n| 2008 || ''[[Wire in the Blood]]'' || Dr. Liam Kerwin || 7 episodes\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Law & Order: UK]]'' || Danny Doyle || Episode: \"Unsafe\"\n|-\n| 2010 || ''One Night in Emergency'' || Mortuary Attendant || Television film\n|-\n| 2010-2019 || ''[[Luther (TV series)|Luther]]'' || Benny Silver |