 Girl]]'' || Physician || \n|-\n| 2008 || ''Terra Firma'' || Quentin || Short film\n|-\n| 2009 || ''[[Down Terrace]]'' || Pringle ||\n|-\n| 2009 || ''Believe'' || Lewis || Short film\n|-\n| 2010 || ''[[Burke and Hare (2010 film)|Burke & Hare]]'' || Patterson ||\n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[Kill List]]'' || Gal || \n|-\n| 2011 || ''[[Big Fat Gypsy Gangster]]'' || Mad Mick || \n|-\n| 2012 || ''[[Shell (film)|Shell]]'' || Hugh ||\n|- \n| 2012 || ''[[The ABCs of Death]]'' || Father Tom || Segment: \"\"U Is for Unearthed\"\n|- \n| 2013 || ''[[For Those in Peril (2013 film)|For Those in Peril]]'' || Frank ||\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[A Field in England]]'' || O'Neil ||\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Svengali (2013 film)|Svengali]]'' || Irish Pierre  ||\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[We Are the Freaks]]'' || Killer Colin ||\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[The World's End (film)|The World's End]]'' || Reverend Green ||\n|-\n| 2014 || ''[[Glassland]]'' || Jim ||\n|-\n| 2014 || ''[[Black Sea (film)|Black Sea]]'' || Reynolds ||\n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[The Hallow]]'' || Garda Davey ||\n|-\n| 2015 ||''[[The Lobster]]'' || Loner Swimmer ||\n|-\n| 2015 || ''Orthodox'' || Shannon ||\n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[My Name is Emily]]'' || Robert ||\n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[Tank 432]]'' || Capper ||\n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[Free Fire]]'' || Frank ||\n|-\n| 2016 || ''[[Rogue One|Rogue One: A Star Wars Story]]'' || Dr. Evazan ||\n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[Madame (2017 film)|Madame]]'' ||  ||\n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[Jawbone (film)|Jawbone]]'' || Eddie ||\n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[Birthmarked (film)|Birthmarked]]'' || Gertz ||\n|-\n| 2018 || ''[[The Nun (2018 film)|The Nun]]'' || Priest ||\n|-\n| 2019 || ''[[Come to Daddy (film)|Come to Daddy]]'' || Jethro ||\n|}\n\n===Radio===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[Toby Swift#Eye Witness|Eye Witness]]'' ||  || [[BBC Radio 3]]\n|-\n| 2007-2009 || ''[[The Maltby Collection]]'' || Des Wainwright || [[BBC Radio 4]]\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|0806968}}\n\n{{BIFA Award for Best Supporting Actor}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Smiley, Michael}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male television actors from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Belfast]]\n[[Category:Male actors from London]]\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century male actors from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Male radio actors from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:Male film actors from Northern Ireland]]\n[[Category:People from Holywood]]\n[[Category:20th-century male actors from Northern Ireland]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=March 2011}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Michael Smiley\n| image        = Michael Smiley (cropped).jpg\n| caption      = Smiley in 2016\n| birth_date   = {{birth year and age|1963}}\n| birth_place  = [[Belfast]], [[Northern Ireland]]\n| occupation   = [[Comedian]] & [[Actor]]\n| spouse       = [[Miranda Sawyer]]\n| children     = 1\n}}\n\n'''Michael Smiley''' (born 1963) is a [[People of Northern Ireland|Northern Irish]] comedian and actor. He is perhaps best known for his roles in the films ''[[Kill List]]'' (2011) and ''[[The Lobster]]'' (2015).\n\n==Early life==\nSmiley was born in 1963 in [[Belfast]] and grew up in [[Holywood]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b01qb0qx/profiles/michael-smiley |title=BBC One - Monumental - Michael Simley |publisher=[[BBC One]] |accessdate=18 August 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/film-tv/news/michael-smiley-im-an-overnight-success-after-20-years-30202335.html|title=Michael Smiley: 'I'm an overnight success after 20 years!'|author=<!-- Staff -->|work=[[Belfast Telegraph]]|date=21 April 2014|accessdate=9 June 2015}}</ref> He moved to [[London]] in his 20s with his wife. He began doing stand-up in 1993, after accepting a bet at an [[open mike|open-mic night]]. He had worked as a [[Bicycle messenger|cycle courier]] (like his character in ''[[Spaced]]'') and as an [[acid house]] [[Disc jockey|DJ]].<ref name=\"EdinburghFestival\">{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/entertainment/edinburgh_festival/146739.stm |title=Living the life of Smiley |date=10 August 1998 |publisher=[[BBC News]] |accessdate=18 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nHe became well known for his role as [[Tyres O'Flaherty]], the bicycle riding raver, in two episodes of the [[Channel 4]] sitcom ''Spaced'', and for his appearances at the [[Edinburgh Fringe]] and the [[Melbourne Comedy Festival]].<ref name=\"EdinburghFestival\"/> He played Mac, a former member of the [[British Army]]'s [[Parachute Regiment (United Kingdom)|Parachute Regiment]] in the 2008 horror film ''[[Outpost (2008 film)|Outpost]]'' and as a zombie in ''[[Shaun of the Dead]]''.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\nIn 2003, he guest starred in the ''[[Doctor Who]]'' audio drama ''[[Creatures of Beauty]]''. In 2004 he appeared in season 2, episode 4 of ''[[Hustle (TV series)|Hustle]]'' as Max the forger.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/tv-programme/e/dvf7q/hustle--s2-e4-missions|title=Hustle - what time is it on TV? Episode 4 Series 2 cast list and preview|website=RadioTimes|access-date=10 September 2016}}</ref> He also was a small character in episode 2 \"The Model\" of ''[[15 Storeys High]]''.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\nHe has appeared in all three series of ''[[The Maltby Collection]]'' on Radio 4 as Des Wainwright, an eccentric security guard who keeps repeating himself and reminding people he was in the [[Special Air Service|SAS]]. He is playing the part of Benny \"Deadhead\" Silver in the BBC drama series ''[[Luther (TV series)|Luther]]''. In 2010, he had a major role in the film ''[[Burke and Hare (2010 film)|Burke & Hare]]'' alongside his ''Spaced'' co-stars [[Simon Pegg]] and [[Jessica Hynes]].\n\nIn 2011, he starred in British horror film ''[[Kill List]]''. The film received critical acclaim, and earned him the [[BIFA Award for Best Supporting Actor|\"Best Supporting Actor\" Award]] at the [[British Independent Film Awards 2011|2011 British Independent Film Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.holymoly.com/film-dvd/pictures/british-independent-film-awards-2011-fassbender-ramsey-sophie-peep-show-win60714|title=British Independent Film Awards 2011: Fassbender, Ramsey & Sophie from Peep Show win|last=Exley|first=Gemma|date=5 December 2012|website=[[Holy Moly]]|accessdate=18 August 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140103231328/http://www.holymoly.com/film-dvd/pictures/british-independent-film-awards-2011-fassbender-ramsey-sophie-peep-show-win60714|archivedate=3 January 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, he has appeared in an episode of [[BBC One]]'s ''[[Ripper Street]]'' as [[George Lusk]], and the critically acclaimed [[Channel 4]] shows ''[[Utopia (UK TV series)|Utopia]]'' as Detective Reynolds and ''[[Black Mirror]]'' as Baxter.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}} He also starred in ''[[A Field in England]]'' as the main antagonist, the alchemist O'Neill. He also played Roddy in ''[[Father Figure (TV series)|Father Figure]]''. In November 2013 he appeared in the third episode of the [[BBC Two]] [[Mitchell and Webb]] comedy ''[[Ambassadors (TV series)|Ambassadors]]'' as Mr Jackson. In 2014, he played Micky Murray in [[BBC Four]]'s ''[[The Life of Rock with Brian Pern]]''.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\nTo coincide with the [[2014 Giro d'Italia, Stage 1 to Stage 11#Stage 1|opening stages]] of the [[Giro d'Italia]] in May 2014, ''Michael Smiley:Something to Ride Home About'' was a [[travelog]] programme for [[BBC Northern Ireland]], directed by [[George Kane (director)|George Kane]], featuring Smiley cycling around Northern Ireland and meeting local people.<ref name=\"ride\">{{cite web|url=http://www.iftn.ie/news/?act1=record&aid=73&force=1&only=1&rid=4287457&tpl=archnews|title=\u2018Michael Smiley: Something To Ride Home About\u2019 Gets Second Series|publisher=[[Irish Film and Television Network]]|date=18 August 2014|accessdate=22 October 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"IrishmanAbroadMS\">{{cite podcast|authorlink=Jarlath Regan|author=Jarlath Regan|edition=7|work=[[An Irishman Abroad]]|title=Michael Smiley|publisher=[[SoundCloud]]|date=14 October 2013|url=https://soundcloud.com/an-irishman-abroad/george-kane-episode-56|accessdate=28 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141215070425/https://soundcloud.com/an-irishman-abroad/george-kane-episode-56|archivedate=15 December 2014}}</ref><ref name=\"IrishmanAbroadGK\">{{cite podcast|authorlink=Jarlath Regan|author=Jarlath Regan|edition=56|work=[[An Irishman Abroad]]|title=George Kane|publisher=[[SoundCloud]]|date=11 June 2014|url=https://soundcloud.com/an-irishman-abroad/george-kane-episode-56|accessdate=28 November 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141215070425/https://soundcloud.com/an-irishman-abroad/george-kane-episode-56|archivedate=15 December 2014}}</ref> A second series has been commissioned for 2015.<ref name=\"ride\"/>\n\nIn 2014 Smiley played Colonel Morgan Blue in the ''[[Doctor Who]]'' episode \"[[Into the Dalek]]\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Mulkern|first=Patrick|date=30 August 2014|title=Into the Dalek ****|url=http://www.radiotimes.com/blog/2014-08-30/into-the-dalek|newspaper=[[Radio Times]]|location=London, UK|accessdate=30 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Smiley also starred in the Netflix show ''[[Black Mirror]]'' as Baxter in \u201c[[White Bear (Black Mirror)|White Bear]]\u201d. He also had a major role in British crime seri''es [[Luther (TV series)]]'' acting as \u201cDeadhead\u201d [[Benny Silver]] from 2010 until 2019.\n\nIn 2019, Smiley co-starred with [[Elijah Wood]] and [[Martin Donovan]] in the film ''[[Come to Daddy (film)|Come to Daddy]]'' directed by [[Ant Timpson]].<ref>[https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/come-daddy-1277024 Come to Daddy Review] by Frank Scheck, The Hollywood Reporter, February 6, 2020.</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nSmiley is married to journalist/broadcaster [[Miranda Sawyer]], with whom he has a son and a daughter. The family lives near Brockwell Park in [[Herne Hill]], [[London]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.notabaddad.com/2013/06/miranda-sawyer-interview|title=Miranda Sawyer Interview|last=Tyler|first=Simon|date=7 June 2013|website=Not a Bad Dad|accessdate=18 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130928184832/http://www.notabaddad.com/2013/06/miranda-sawyer-interview/|archive-date=28 September 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> He shared a flat with [[Simon Pegg]] and [[Nick Frost]] in the 1990s.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.echo-news.co.uk/news/9103419.welcome-to-the-bonkers-world-of-michael-smiley/|title=Welcome to the bonkers world of Michael Smiley|last=Marsh|first=Hannah|date=|newspaper=[[The Echo (Essex)|The Echo]]|accessdate=18 August 2013|location=[[Basildon]]}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography ==\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| 1989 || ''[[The Heist (1989 film)|The Heist]]'' || Detective || Television film; uncredited\n|-\n| 2000 || ''[[Burnside (TV series)|Burnside]]'' || Matthew Hutchins || Episode: \"Back with a Vengeance: Part 1\"\n|-\n| 1999-2001 || ''[[Spaced]]'' || [[Tyres O'Flaherty]] || 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2000-2002 || ''[[Time Gentlemen Please]]'' || Martin || 3 episodes\n|-\n| 2002 || ''[[15 Storeys High]]'' || Insistent Irish visitor || Episode: \"The Model\"\n|-\n| 2004 || ''[[Murder Prevention]]'' || DC Maurice Gibney || 4 episodes\n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[Bleak House]]'' || Phil Squod || 8 episodes\n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[Hustle (TV series)|Hustle]]'' || Max || Episode: \"Missions\"\n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[ShakespeaRe-Told]]'' || Peter || Episode: \"[[Much Ado About Nothing]]\"\n|-\n| 2005 || ''[[Rose and Maloney]]'' || DS Mallam || Episode: \"Rise & Fall\"\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[In the Spider's Web]]'' || Phil || Television film\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[Y Pr