016/09/MoralizationPS1999-1y8a9bo.pdf|journal=Psychological Science|volume=10|issue=3|pages=218\u2013221|doi=10.1111/1467-9280.00139|via=}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Rozin|first1=P.|last2=Lowery|first2=L.|last3=Imada|first3=S.|last4=Haidt|first4=J.|year=1999|title=The CAD triad hypothesis: A mapping between three moral emotions (contempt, anger, disgust) and three moral codes (community, autonomy, divinity)|url=http://faculty.virginia.edu/haidtlab/articles/rozin.lowery.1999.moral-emotion-triad-hypothesis.pub012.pdf|journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology|volume=76|issue=4|pages=574\u2013586|doi=10.1037/0022-3514.76.4.574|via=}}\n*{{cite journal|last1=Rozin|first1=P.|last2=Markwith|first2=M.|last3=Stoess|first3=C.|year=1997|title=Moralization and becoming a vegetarian: The transformation of preferences into values and the recruitment of disgust|url=http://foodethics.univie.ac.at/fileadmin/user_upload/inst_ethik_wiss_dialog/Rozin__.._1997._Moralization_and_becoming_a_vegetarian_in__psychological_science.pdf|journal=Psychological Science|volume=8|issue=2|pages=67\u201373|doi=10.1111/j.1467-9280.1997.tb00685.x|via=}}\n* {{cite book|last=Smith|first=Michael A.|title=The Moral Problem|location=Oxford|pages=|year=2004|oclc=451103422|publisher=Blackwell|isbn=978-0-631-18941-1}} \n* {{cite journal|last1=Tetlock|first1=P.|last2=Kristel|first2=O.|last3=Elson|first3=B.|last4=Green|first4=M.|last5=Lerner|first5=J.|year=2000|title=The Psychology of the Unthinkable: Taboo Trade-Offs, Forbidden Base Rates, and Heretical Counterfactuals|url=https://www.academia.edu/download/44267432/The_Psychology_of_the_Unthinkable_Taboo_20160331-28670-1witok7.pdf|journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology|volume=78|issue=5|pages=853\u2013870|doi=10.1037/0022-3514.78.5.853|via=|citeseerx=10.1.1.126.6275}}\n* {{cite journal|last1=Thagard|first1=Paul|year=2007|title=The Moral Psychology of Conflicts of Interest: Insights from Affective Neuroscience|url=http://watarts.uwaterloo.ca/~pthagard/Articles/moral-psych.2007.pdf|journal=Journal of Applied Philosophy|volume=24|issue=4|pages=367\u2013380|doi=10.1111/j.1468-5930.2007.00382.x|via=}}\n*{{cite book|last=Wallace|first=R. Jay|title=Normativity and the Will: Selected Essays on Moral Psychology and Practical Reason|year=2006|publisher=Clarendon Press|isbn=978-0-19-153699-1|location=|pages=}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Library resources box|by=no|onlinebooks=no|wikititle=moral psychology}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commonscat}}\n*[http://www.moralpsychology.net/group/ Moral Psychology Research Group] \u2013 with Knobe, Nichols, Doris and others.\n\n; From the ''[[Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy]]'':\n*[http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/empathy/ Empathy]\n*[http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/moral-character/ Moral Character] \n*[http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/moral-motivation/ Moral Motivation]\n*[http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/moral-psych-emp/ Moral Psychology: Empirical Approaches]\n*[http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/moral-responsibility/ Moral Responsibility]\n\n; From the ''[[Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy]]'': \n*[http://www.iep.utm.edu/e/ethics.htm#SH1b Psychological Issues in Metaethics]\n*[http://www.iep.utm.edu/m/moral-ch.htm Moral Character]\n*[http://www.iep.utm.edu/m/moraldev.htm Moral Development]\n*[http://www.iep.utm.edu/r/responsi.htm Responsibility]\n\n{{Psychology}}\n{{Ethics}}\n\n[[Category:Moral psychology| ]]\n[[Category:Ethics]]\n[[Category:Philosophy of mind]]\n", "name_user": "Lcscnc", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eHistory:minor copy editing", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moral_psychology"}
{"title_page": "Disposable food packaging", "text_new": "[[Image:McDonalds Molded Pulp Drink Tray Top.jpg|thumb|[[Molded pulp]] drink carrier]]\n[[Image:BiodegradablePlasticUtensils1.jpg|thumb|Biodegradable plastic [[Kitchen utensil|utensil]]s]]\n[[File:Butter single portion in container.JPG|thumb|A single-serving packet of butter]]\n[[File:Fish n chips.jpg|thumb|Fish and Chips: wrapped in [[wax paper]] then with used [[newspaper]], packets of condiments]]\n\n'''Disposable food packaging''' comprises disposable items often found in [[fast food restaurant]]s, [[Takeaway|takeout restaurants]] and [[kiosk]]s, and [[catering]] establishments. Food-serving items for picnics and parties are very similar. Typical disposable [[foodservice]] products are [[foam food container]]s, plates, bowls, [[disposable cup|cups]], utensils, doilies and tray papers. These products can be made from a number of materials including [[plastics]], [[paper]], bioresins, wood and [[bamboo]].\n\nPackaging of fast food and take-out food involves a significant amount of material that ends up in [[landfill]], [[recycling]], [[composting]] or [[litter]].<ref>{{Citation| title =Reducing Wasted Food & Packaging: A Guide for Food Services and Restaurants| publisher =US Environmental Protection Agency| volume =EPA-909-K-14-002| url =http://www.epa.gov/waste/conserve/foodwaste/docs/reducing_wasted_food_pkg_tool.pdf| access-date =9 March 2015| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20150318103240/http://www.epa.gov/waste/conserve/foodwaste/docs/reducing_wasted_food_pkg_tool.pdf| archivedate =18 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe [[paper plate]] was invented by the German bookbinder [[Hermann Henschel]] in [[Luckenwalde]] in 1867.\n\nIn 1908, Samuel J. Crumbine<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kshs.org/portraits/crumbine_samuel.htm|title=Samuel J. Crumbine - Kansapedia - Kansas Historical Society|author=|date=|work=KsHS.org|access-date=4 April 2017}}</ref> was a [[public health]] officer in [[Kansas]]. He was on a train when he witnessed one of his [[tuberculosis]] patients taking a drink of water from a common dipper and water bucket (a publicly shared way of drinking water) in the car. Right behind his patient was a young girl who drank from the same dipper and bucket. This inspired him to launch a crusade to ban publicly shared or common utensils in public places. Taking note of the trend, Lawrence Luellen and [[Hugh Moore (businessman)|Hugh Moore]] invented a disposable [[paper cup]] called the \"Health Cup\" and later renamed the  \"[[Dixie Cup]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://academicmuseum.lafayette.edu/special/dixie/company.html |title=Dixie Cup Company History |publisher=Lafayette College Libraries |date=August 1995 |access-date=5 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111112065042/http://academicmuseum.lafayette.edu/special/dixie/company.html |archive-date=12 November 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>''Food and Drink Quarterly'', Vol 4 Issue 4, \"Package Perfect\" By John Burke</ref>\n\n[[Single-use]] cone cups were followed by the commercialization of single-use plates and bowls, wooden [[cutlery]], and paper food wraps. By the 1930s these products were widely used to feed the men and women who worked on the remote dams, bridges, and roads of the [[Works Progress Administration]]. In the 1940s they were used to feed defense factory workers.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">Foodservice Packaging Institute, \"A Brief History of Foodservice Packaging\", 2006</ref>\n\nAfter [[World War II]], foodservice packaging materials like [[plastic]] and [[polystyrene foam]] were developed. The unique properties of these materials (insulation and weight reduction) and their ability to be made into a variety of shapes and sizes, provided foodservice operators, and consumers, with a wider variety of packaging choices.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\" />\n\nA major development in disposable foodservice packaging happened in 1948 when the newly founded [[McDonald's]] restaurant closed to revamp its menu. Along with changing their menu items, the restaurant wanted to change the way it handled dishwashing and [[dishwasher]]s, carhops and wait staff, and storage, breakage and (customer) theft of tableware. When the McDonald's re-opened six months later, its meals were no longer served with the use of glasses, plates or cutlery, and were taken away from the restaurant by the customers.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\" />\n\n== Sanitation ==\nThe use of disposable [[foodservice]] [[packaging]] is a step toward preventing [[Foodborne illness|foodborne disease]]. By being used only once, these products significantly reduce [[food contamination]] and the spread of diseases.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|date=October 5, 2007|title=US FDA/CFSAN FDA Food Code|url=http://www.foodsafety.gov/~dms/foodcode.html |website=FoodSafety.gov|access-date=March 23, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327074554/http://www.foodsafety.gov/~dms/foodcode.html |archivedate=March 27, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[U.S. Food and Drug Administration]]\u2019s [[Food code#United States|Food Code]] authoritatively spells out the [[sanitary]] and health advantages of single-use foodservice packaging in specific situations: \"A food establishment without facilities...for cleaning and sanitizing [[kitchenware]] and [[tableware]] shall provide only single-use kitchenware, single-service articles, and single-use articles for use by food employees and single-service articles for use by consumers.\" The Food Code further states \"in situations in which the reuse of multiuse items could result in foodborne illness to consumers, single-service and single-use articles must be used to ensure safety.\"<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\n== Materials ==\n[[File:Insulated paper cup cutaway.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Insulated [[paper cup]] for hot drinks, cut away to show air layer]]\n[[File:Oysterpail.jpg|thumb|Rice in a paperboard [[oyster pail]]]]\n[[Image:Yummp hk lunchbox.jpg|thumb|right|[[Siu mei]] with rice in a [[foam food container]]]]\nDisposable foodservice packaging can be made from a number of materials, each with its own uses and benefits.\n\n=== Aluminum ===\n[[Aluminum]] is used to manufacture foils, wraps, bags, containers, and [[aluminium tray|trays]].\n\n=== Plastics ===\n{{see also|Foam food container}}\nMany disposable foodservice products can be made of [[plastic]] or [[plastic-coated paper]]: [[plastic cup|cups]], plates, bowls, trays, food containers and [[disposable cutlery|cutlery]], for example. Plastics are used because the material is lightweight and holds the temperature of hot/cold food and beverages. Foamed [[polystyrene]] (sometimes referred to as Styrofoam) is in one of the most common types of plastics used for foodservice packaging, in the form of the [[foam food container]]. Non-foamed polystyrene is sometimes also used for utensils or plastic plates. [[Polyethylene]] and other plastics are also used.\n\n[[Plastic wrap]] is sometimes used to cover a tray of food.\n\nMany plastics are marked with the [[Society of the Plastics Industry|SPI]] [[recycling code]]s for identification.\n\n=== Paper and paperboard ===\n[[File:The Giant hamburger, fries and soda - Quick.jpg|thumb|Paperboard clamshell for fast food]]\nDisposable food service products made from [[paper]], [[paperboard]], and [[corrugated fiberboard]]:  including cups, plates, bowls, napkins, carryout bags, trays, [[egg carton]]s, doilies and tray liners. Some paper products are [[coated paper|coated]] - mostly with [[plastic-coated paper|plastic]] - or treated to improve wet strength or grease resistance. Paper and paperboard packaging like pizza trays, French fry trays, Chinese noodle soup boxes, hamburger clamshell trays, etc., are developed by printers utilizing paper-converting equipment such as tray formers.\n\n[[Molded pulp]]  products are made from recycled [[newsprint]] and are formed under heat and pressure into plates, bowls, trays, and cup carriers. Molded pulp is readily recyclable.\n\n=== Wood and Bamboo ===\n[[File:Foodstiks Wood Fork.jpg|thumb|Disposable Wood Fork <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0076/6201/0425/files/FoodstiksForkFood_B07JHC182S_1.jpg?v=1542055956|website=cdn.shopify.com|access-date=2018-12-21}}</ref>]]\nIn recent years, manufacturers have been working on developing more sustainable alternatives to traditional plastic products. Among them are plates and cutlery (mostly birch) made of bamboo and wood. Throughout the entire life cycle of wood products, there can be far fewer environmental repercussions than with traditional plastics, and possibly fewer with bioplastics like PLA, which composts into lactic acid.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foodstiks.com/blogs/news/how-sustainable-are-plastic-cutlery-alternatives|title=How sustainable are plastic cutlery alternatives?|website=foodstiks|access-date=2018-12-21}}</ref> Wooden products decompose on average in the matter of a few months. Currently, wood and bamboo products are more costly than traditional plastics and not as widely available, which makes it challenging for some restaurants to switch.\n\n=== Alternative materials ===\nA number of manufacturers are now making disposable foodservice products from a combination of natural [[starch]]es, recycled fibers, water, air, and natural minerals.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Foodservice Packaging Institute, \"Single-Use Foodservice Packaging: A Tutorial\", 2007</ref> These composite products include cups, plates, bowls, cutlery, sandwich wraps, food containers, and trays. Ideally, these products are easily [[biodegradable]] and composted after use.\n\nThe material used to make these kinds of disposable foodservice products is primarily PLA or [[polylactic acid]]. Some products are made from a mixture of PLA and pulp fibers that are molded into disposable foodservice items with heat and pressure. Others are made from a composite or mixture of starch and other materials, such as [[limestone]] and recycled [[fibers]], to give them additional strength.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nAreca palm plates are made from dry fallen leaves from the [[Areca catechu]] palm (betel tree). These trees shed the old dried leaves along with their sheath. These sheaths are separated from leaves and sent to the factory. The sheaths are then soaked and washed in clean water to remove the dust and sand particles. The sheaths are hot-pressed and made into areca palm plates, bowls, and food containers. Compared to other disposable items, areca palm products are 100% natural, eco-friendly. No synthetic adhesives or binders used in the manufacturing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crozborder.com/areca-palm-leaf-plates-manufacturing-process/|title=How areca palm products are made?|last=|first=|date=2019-11-05|website=CrozBorder|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n[[File:500ml areca palm food container .jpg|thumb]]\n<br />\n\n== Cost ==\nBy reducing the need for equipment and additional labor, disposable foodservice packaging is an economical alternative to multiuse items and eliminates the need for dishwashers and other support equipment (racks, carts, dollies, shelving, bins). It can also save money on water and energy used by dishwashers and can eliminate the need to replace reusables that are broken, damaged, stolen or accidentally discarded.<ref>[http://fpi.org/dms/Main.asp Library<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214001303/http://fpi.org/dms/Main.asp |date=February 14, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n== Other Economics ==\n[[Disposable tableware]] was a key part of the business strategy of chain [[fast food]] restaurants in the US. In order for the business model to work, fast food chains, notably [[McDonald's]], had to convince consumers<ref name=\"dontbus\">{{cite web|url=http://www.skoozeme.com/issues/dontbus.html|title=Don't Bus Throw-Away Utensils and Tableware|website=www.skoozeme.com|accessdate=21 May 2019}}</ref> through advertising campaigns to carry their own tableware to waste bins, in order to avoid labor expenses incurred in clearing tables. By establishing a custom in which customers are encouraged to carry disposables, some of the internal costs of the disposable tableware can be offset.\n\n== Environmental concerns ==\n[[File:Coffee-cup-sleeve.jpg|thumb|[[Coffee cup sleeve]] on a coffee cup; sleeve makes it easy to hold hot drinks.]]\n{{see|plastic waste|litter}}\n\n=== Comparison with washable foodservice products ===\nAccording to the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|U.S. Environmental Protection Agency]], paper and plastic foodservice packaging discarded in the country's [[municipal solid waste]] stream accounted 1.3 percent in 2007 (by weight) of municipal solid waste.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.epa.gov/epawaste/nonhaz/municipal/index.htm|title=Advancing Sustainable Materials Management: Facts and Figures|first=US|last=EPA,OSWER,ORCR|date=2015-09-22|work=EPA.gov|access-date=4 April 2017}}</ref> The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency also says that an often-cited [[waste prevention]] measure is the use of washable plates, cups, and napkins instead of the disposable variety.\n\nWhile this will reduce solid waste, it will have other environmental effects, such as increased water and [[Energy|energy use]]. Overall, reusable dishware \u2013 even if only offered to customers for on-site use \u2013 is considered to be the best environmental choice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.portlandoregon.gov/sustainabilityatwork/article/507465|title=Disposable Cups, Cutlery and Dishware|work=Resource Guide, Sustainability at work|publisher=City of Portland|date=2014|accessdate=2017-08-31}}</ref>\n\n=== Cost of recycling ===\nCollection costs, the value of scrap material, and increased energy expenditures create an additional economic barrier to recycling foodservice packaging. While recycling foodservice packaging is difficult, recycled materials are being used in some foodservice packaging.\n\n=== Environmental footprint ===\nMany people are working on reducing the [[environmental footprint]] of packaging for food service. Often a [[Life-cycle assessment]] is valuable to determine the effects throughout the entire system. Some actions include:\n* Packaging of incoming food and supplies can work towards the broad [[sustainable packaging]] guidelines offered by many organizations. This includes the recycling of packaging generated within the restaurant.\n* Packaging products used by the restaurant can include specified amounts of recycled content in the products.\n* Many packaging products can be [[compostable]], but care is needed to match the needs of  regional composting facilities. Sometimes products can be certified<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bpiworld.org|title=Biodegradable Products Institute - Certified Compostable|author=|date=|work=BPIWorld.org|access-date=4 April 2017}}</ref> to meet international standards such as [[ASTM International]] D6400, ASTM D6868, and EN 13432.<ref>{{Citation\n | last = Dietz\n | first = C\n | title = Compostable Products for Food Services\n | publisher = Eco-Cycle\n | date=February 2013\n | url = http://www.ecocycle.org/files/pdfs/compostable_products_for_food_services.pdf\n }}</ref>\n* Some single-use food packaging is recyclable but [[food contamination]] of products is often a problem for recyclers.<ref>{{cite web |author=Raymond J. Ehrlich |date=2007 |url=http://www.americanchemistry.com/s_plastics/sec_pfpg.asp?CID%3D1436%26DID%3D5228 |title=Plastics Foodservice Packaging Group : Economic Realities of Recycling |access-date=23 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090111102714/http://www.americanchemistry.com/s_plastics/sec_pfpg.asp?CID=1436&DID=5228 |archivedate=2009-01-11 }} </ref>\n\n===Illusion of recycling and \"recyclable\" claims===\n{{Main|Greenwashing}}\nDisposable-product manufacturers frequently include \"recyclable\" or \"please recycle\" indicia on their products; however the availability and effectiveness of such recycling campaigns is limited.<ref name=\"mahb\">[https://mahb.stanford.edu/blog/environmental-ineffectiveness/ Environmental Ineffectiveness], Millennium Alliance for Humanity and Biosphere (MAHB)</ref> A common approach of restaurants featuring disposable tableware is to label one or more of their waste bins as \"recycling\", although realistically, the amount of washing required for effective recycling would make such \"recycling\" unrealistic.<ref name=\"recyclebank\">[https://livegreen.recyclebank.com/because-you-asked-why-can-t-i-recycle-stuff-with-food-on-it Because You Asked: Why Can\u2019t I Recycle Stuff with Food On It?], recyclebank.com</ref><ref name=\"motherjones_clean\">[https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2011/02/clean-food-containers-recycling/ How Clean Must Food Containers Be Before Recycling?], Mother Jones</ref> In addition to [[greenwashing]], these approaches are intended to encourage consumers to bus disposable tableware. Some experts view a total ban of single-use packaging as the only solution. For example, the Chinese government stated that by the end of 2020, non-degradable bags will be banned in major cities, and by 2022, the policy will come into force in smaller settlements.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51171491|title=Single-use plastic: China to ban bags and other items|last=|first=|date=20 January 2020|website=BBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Disposable tableware]]\n* [[Drinking straw]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{packaging}}\n\n[[Category:Food packaging]]\n[[Category:Fast food]]\n[[Category:Disposable products]]\n[[Category:Food waste]]\n[[Category:Single-serve containers]]\n", "text_old": "[[Image:McDonalds Molded Pulp Drink Tray Top.jpg|thumb|[[Molded pulp]] drink carrier]]\n[[Image:BiodegradablePlasticUtensils1.jpg|thumb|Biodegradable plastic [[Kitchen utensil|utensil]]s]]\n[[File:Butter single portion in container.JPG|thumb|A single-serving packet of butter]]\n[[File:Fish n chips.jpg|thumb|Fish and Chips: wrapped in [[wax paper]] then with used [[newspaper]], packets of condiments]]\n\n'''Disposable food packaging''' comprises disposable items often found in [[fast food restaurant]]s, [[Takeaway|takeout restaurants]] and [[kiosk]]s, and [[catering]] establishments. Food-serving items for picnics and parties are very similar. Typical disposable [[foodservice]] products are [[foam food container]]s, plates, bowls, [[disposable cup|cups]], utensils, doilies and tray papers. These products can be made from a number of materials including [[plastics]], [[paper]], bioresins, wood and [[bamboo]].\n\nPackaging of fast food and take-out food involves a significant amount of material that ends up in [[landfill]], [[recycling]], [[composting]] or [[litter]].<ref>{{Citation| title =Reducing Wasted Food & Packaging: A Guide for Food Services and Restaurants| publisher =US Environmental Protection Agency| volume =EPA-909-K-14-002| url =http://www.epa.gov/waste/conserve/foodwaste/docs/reducing_wasted_food_pkg_tool.pdf| access-date =9 March 2015| url-status =dead| archiveurl =https://web.archive.org/web/20150318103240/http://www.epa.gov/waste/conserve/foodwaste/docs/reducing_wasted_food_pkg_tool.pdf| archivedate =18 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe [[paper plate]] was invented by the German bookbinder [[Hermann Henschel]] in [[Luckenwalde]] in 1867.\n\nIn 1908, Samuel J. Crumbine<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kshs.org/portraits/crumbine_samuel.htm|title=Samuel J. Crumbine - Kansapedia - Kansas Historical Society|author=|date=|work=KsHS.org|access-date=4 April 2017}}</ref> was a [[public health]] officer in [[Kansas]]. He was on a train when he witnessed one of his [[tuberculosis]] patients taking a drink of water from a common dipper and water bucket (a publicly shared way of drinking water) in the car. Right behind his patient was a young girl who drank from the same dipper and bucket. This inspired him to launch a crusade to ban publicly shared or common utensils in public places. Taking note of the trend, Lawrence Luellen and [[Hugh Moore (businessman)|Hugh Moore]] invented a disposable [[paper cup]] called the \"Health Cup\" and later renamed the  \"[[Dixie Cup]]\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://academicmuseum.lafayette.edu/special/dixie/company.html |title=Dixie Cup Company History |publisher=Lafayette College Libraries |date=August 1995 |access-date=5 October 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111112065042/http://academicmuseum.lafayette.edu/special/dixie/company.html |archive-date=12 November 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>''Food and Drink Quarterly'', Vol 4 Issue 4, \"Package Perfect\" By John Burke</ref>\n\n[[Single-use]] cone cups were followed by the commercialization of single-use plates and bowls, wooden [[cutlery]], and paper food wraps. By the 1930s these products were widely used to feed the men and women who worked on the remote dams, bridges and roads of the [[Works Progress Administration]]. In the 1940s they were used to feed defense factory workers.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\">Foodservice Packaging Institute, \"A Brief History of Foodservice Packaging\", 2006</ref>\n\nAfter [[World War II]], foodservice packaging materials like [[plastic]] and [[polystyrene foam]] were developed. The unique properties of these materials (insulation and weight reduction) and their ability to be made into a variety of shapes and sizes, provided foodservice operators, and consumers, with a wider variety of packaging choices.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\" />\n\nA major development in disposable foodservice packaging happened in 1948 when the newly founded [[McDonald's]] restaurant closed to revamp its menu. Along with changing their menu items, the restaurant wanted to change the way it handled dishwashing and [[dishwasher]]s, car hops and wait staff, and storage, breakage and (customer) theft of table ware. When the McDonald's re-opened six months later, its meals were no longer served with the use of glasses, plates or cutlery, and were taken away from the restaurant by the customers.<ref name=\"autogenerated2\" />\n\n== Sanitation ==\nThe use of disposable [[foodservice]] [[packaging]] is a step toward preventing [[Foodborne illness|foodborne disease]]. By being used only once, these products significantly reduce [[food contamination]] and the spread of diseases.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|date=October 5, 2007|title=US FDA/CFSAN FDA Food Code|url=http://www.foodsafety.gov/~dms/foodcode.html |website=FoodSafety.gov|access-date=March 23, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327074554/http://www.foodsafety.gov/~dms/foodcode.html |archivedate=March 27, 2009 }}</ref>\n\nThe [[U.S. Food and Drug Administration]]\u2019s [[Food code#United States|Food Code]] authoritatively spells out the [[sanitary]] and health advantages of single-use foodservice packaging in specific situations: \"A food establishment without facilities...for cleaning and sanitizing [[kitchenware]] and [[tableware]] shall provide only single-use kitchenware, single-service articles, and single-use articles for use by food employees and single-service articles for use by consumers.\" The Food Code further states \"in situations in which the reuse of multiuse items could result in foodborne illness to consumers, single-service and single-use articles must be used to ensure safety.\"<ref name=\"autogenerated1\" />\n\n== Materials ==\n[[File:Insulated paper cup cutaway.JPG|thumb|right|200px|Insulated [[paper cup]] for hot drinks, cut away to show air layer]]\n[[File:Oysterpail.jpg|thumb|Rice in a paperboard [[oyster pail]]]]\n[[Image:Yummp hk lunchbox.jpg|thumb|right|[[Siu mei]] with rice in a [[foam food container]]]]\nDisposable foodservice packaging can be made from a number of materials, each with its own uses and benefits.\n\n=== Aluminum ===\n[[Aluminum]] is used to manufacture foils, wraps, bags, containers, and [[aluminium tray|trays]].\n\n=== Plastics ===\n{{see also|Foam food container}}\nMany disposable foodservice products can be made of [[plastic]] or [[plastic-coated paper]]: [[plastic cup|cups]], plates, bowls, trays, food containers and [[disposable cutlery|cutlery]], for example. Plastics are used because the material is lightweight and holds the temperature of hot/cold food and beverages. Foamed [[polystyrene]] (sometimes referred to as Styrofoam) is in one of the most common types of plastics used for foodservice packaging, in the form of the [[foam food container]]. Non-foamed polystyrene is sometimes also used for utensils or plastic plates. [[Polyethylene]] and other plastics are also used.\n\n[[Plastic wrap]] is sometimes used to cover a tray of food.\n\nMany plastics are marked with the [[Society of the Plastics Industry|SPI]] [[recycling code]]s for identification.\n\n=== Paper and paperboard ===\n[[File:The Giant hamburger, fries and soda - Quick.jpg|thumb|Paperboard clamshell for fast food]]\nDisposable foodservice products made from [[paper]], [[paperboard]], and [[corrugated fiberboard]]:  including cups, plates, bowls, napkins, carryout bags, trays, [[egg carton]]s, doilies and tray liners. Some paper products are [[coated paper|coated]] - mostly with [[plastic-coated paper|plastic]] - or treated to improve wet strength or grease resistance. Paper and paperboard packaging like pizza trays, French fry trays, Chinese noodle soup boxes, hamburger clamshell trays, etc., are developed by printers utilizing paper-converting equipment such as tray formers.\n\n[[Molded pulp]]  products are made from recycled [[newsprint]] and are formed under heat and pressure into plates, bowls, trays and cup carriers. Molded pulp is readily recyclable.\n\n=== Wood and Bamboo ===\n[[File:Foodstiks Wood Fork.jpg|thumb|Disposable Wood Fork <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0076/6201/0425/files/FoodstiksForkFood_B07JHC182S_1.jpg?v=1542055956|website=cdn.shopify.com|access-date=2018-12-21}}</ref>]]\nIn recent years, manufacturers have been working on developing more sustainable alternatives to traditional plastic products. Amongst them are plates and cutlery made from bamboo and wood (mostly birch). Throughout the entire life cycle of wood products, there can be far fewer environmental repercussions than with traditional plastics, and possibly fewer with bioplastics like PLA, which composts into lactic acid.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://foodstiks.com/blogs/news/how-sustainable-are-plastic-cutlery-alternatives|title=How sustainable are plastic cutlery alternatives?|website=foodstiks|access-date=2018-12-21}}</ref> Wooden  products decompose on average in the matter of a few months. Currently wood and bamboo products are more costly than traditional plastics and not as widely available, which makes it challenging for some restaurants to switch.\n\n=== Alternative materials ===\nA number of manufacturers are now making disposable foodservice products from a combination of natural [[starch]]es, recycled fibers, water, air, and natural minerals.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Foodservice Packaging Institute, \"Single-Use Foodservice Packaging: A Tutorial\", 2007</ref> These composite products include cups, plates, bowls, cutlery, sandwich wraps, food containers and trays. Ideally these products are easily [[biodegradable]] and composted after use.\n\nThe material used to make these kinds of disposable foodservice products is primarily PLA or [[polylactic acid]]. Some products are made from a mixture of PLA and pulp fibers that are molded into disposable foodservice items with heat and pressure. Others are made from a composite or mixture of starch and other materials, such as [[limestone]] and recycled [[fibers]], to give them additional strength.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\nAreca palm plates are made from dry fallen leaves from the [[Areca catechu]] palm (betel tree). This trees shed the old dried leaves along with their sheath. These sheaths are separated from leaves and sent to the factory. The sheaths are then soaked and washed in clean water to remove the dust and sand particles. The sheaths are hot pressed and made into areca palm plates, bowls and food containers. Compared to other disposable items, areca palm products are 100% natural, eco-friendly. No synthetic adhesives or binders used in the manufacturing.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.crozborder.com/areca-palm-leaf-plates-manufacturing-process/|title=How areca palm products are made?|last=|first=|date=2019-11-05|website=CrozBorder|language=en-US|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n[[File:500ml areca palm food container .jpg|thumb]]\n<br />\n\n== Cost ==\nBy reducing the need for equipment and additional labor, disposable foodservice packaging is an economical alternative to multiuse items and eliminates the need for dishwashers and other support equipment (racks, carts, dollies, shelving, bins). It can also save money on water and energy used by dishwashers and can eliminate the need to replace reusables that are broken, damaged, stolen or accidentally discarded.<ref>[http://fpi.org/dms/Main.asp Library<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214001303/http://fpi.org/dms/Main.asp |date=February 14, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n== Other Economics ==\n[[Disposable tableware]] was a key part of the business strategy of chain [[fast food]] restaurants in the US. In order for the business model to work, fast food chains, notably [[McDonald's]], had to convince consumers<ref name=\"dontbus\">{{cite web|url=http://www.skoozeme.com/issues/dontbus.html|title=Don't Bus Throw-Away Utensils and Tableware|website=www.skoozeme.com|accessdate=21 May 2019}}</ref> through advertising campaigns to carry their own tableware to a waste bins, in order to avoid labor expenses incurred in clearing tables. By establishing a custom in which customers are encouraged to carry disposables, some of the internal costs of the disposable tableware can be offset.\n\n== Environmental concerns ==\n[[File:Coffee-cup-sleeve.jpg|thumb|[[Coffee cup sleeve]] on a coffee cup; sleeve makes it easy to hold hot drinks.]]\n{{see|plastic waste|litter}}\n\n=== Comparison with washable foodservice products ===\nAccording to the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|U.S. Environmental Protection Agency]], paper and plastic foodservice packaging discarded in the country's [[municipal solid waste]] stream accounted 1.3 percent in 2007 (by weight) of municipal solid waste.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.epa.gov/epawaste/nonhaz/municipal/index.htm|title=Advancing Sustainable Materials Management: Facts and Figures|first=US|last=EPA,OSWER,ORCR|date=2015-09-22|work=EPA.gov|access-date=4 April 2017}}</ref> The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency also says that an often-cited [[waste prevention]] measure is the use of washable plates, cups, and napkins instead of the disposable variety.\n\nWhile this will reduce solid waste, it will have other environmental effects, such as increased water and [[Energy|energy use]]. Overall, reusable dishware \u2013 even if only offered to customers for on-site use \u2013 is considered to be the best environmental choice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.portlandoregon.gov/sustainabilityatwork/article/507465|title=Disposable Cups, Cutlery and Dishware|work=Resource Guide, Sustainability at work|publisher=City of Portland|date=2014|accessdate=2017-08-31}}</ref>\n\n=== Cost of recycling ===\nCollection costs, the value of scrap material, and increased energy expenditures create an additional economic barrier to recycling foodservice packaging. While recycling foodservice packaging is difficult, recycled materials are being used in some foodservice packaging.\n\n=== Environmental footprint ===\nMany people are working on reducing the [[environmental footprint]] of packaging for food service. Often a [[Life-cycle assessment]] is valuable to determine the effects throughout the entire system. Some actions include:\n* Packaging of incoming food and supplies can work towards the broad [[sustainable packaging]] guidelines offered by many organizations. This includes the recycling of packaging generated within the restaurant.\n* Packaging products used by the restaurant can include specified amounts of recycled content in the products.\n* Many packaging products can be [[compostable]], but care is needed to match the needs of  regional composting facilities. Sometimes products can be certified<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bpiworld.org|title=Biodegradable Products Institute - Certified Compostable|author=|date=|work=BPIWorld.org|access-date=4 April 2017}}</ref> to meet international standards such as [[ASTM International]] D6400, ASTM D6868, and EN 13432.<ref>{{Citation\n | last = Dietz\n | first = C\n | title = Compostable Products for Food Services\n | publisher = Eco-Cycle\n | date=February 2013\n | url = http://www.ecocycle.org/files/pdfs/compostable_products_for_food_services.pdf\n }}</ref>\n* Some single-use food packaging is recyclable but [[food contamination]] of products is often a problem for recyclers.<ref>{{cite web |author=Raymond J. Ehrlich |date=2007 |url=http://www.americanchemistry.com/s_plastics/sec_pfpg.asp?CID%3D1436%26DID%3D5228 |title=Plastics Foodservice Packaging Group : Economic Realities of Recycling |access-date=23 March 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090111102714/http://www.americanchemistry.com/s_plastics/sec_pfpg.asp?CID=1436&DID=5228 |archivedate=2009-01-11 }} </ref>\n\n===Illusion of recycling and \"recyclable\" claims===\n{{Main|Greenwashing}}\nDisposable-product manufacturers frequently include \"recyclable\" or \"please recycle\" indicia on their products; however the availability and effectiveness of such recycling campaigns is limited.<ref name=\"mahb\">[https://mahb.stanford.edu/blog/environmental-ineffectiveness/ Environmental Ineffectiveness], Millennium Alliance for Humanity and Biosphere (MAHB)</ref> A common approach of restaurants featuring disposable tableware is to label one or more of their waste bins as \"recycling\", although realistically, the amount of washing required for effective recycling would make such \"recycling\" unrealistic.<ref name=\"recyclebank\">[https://livegreen.recyclebank.com/because-you-asked-why-can-t-i-recycle-stuff-with-food-on-it Because You Asked: Why Can\u2019t I Recycle Stuff with Food On It?], recyclebank.com</ref><ref name=\"motherjones_clean\">[https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2011/02/clean-food-containers-recycling/ How Clean Must Food Containers Be Before Recycling?], Mother Jones</ref> In addition to [[greenwashing]], these approaches are intended to encourage consumers to bus disposable tableware. Some experts view a total ban of single-use packaging as the only solution. For example, the Chinese government stated that by the end of 2020, non-degradable bags will be banned in major cities, and by 2022, the policy will come into force in smaller settlements.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-china-51171491|title=Single-use plastic: China to ban bags and other items|last=|first=|date=20 January 2020|website=BBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Disposable tableware]]\n* [[Drinking straw]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{packaging}}\n\n[[Category:Food packaging]]\n[[Category:Fast food]]\n[[Category:Disposable products]]\n[[Category:Food waste]]\n[[Category:Single-serve containers]]\n", "name_user": "Ravitavethiya", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Disposable_food_packaging"}
